<DOCNO> AP900509-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
political power and billions of dollars are at 
stake in a battle over which final census numbers will be better 
the raw or the cooked the actual count or one adjusted for people 
who were probably missed 
its an argument thats been obscured by the early problems 
plaguing the census count 
but a year from now the question of adjusting the results 
of the census could be the center of a crucial and bitter debate 
among the states and cities in congress and in the courts 
they cant beat us out so they want to count us out john 
d rogers a republican floor leader in the kentucky senate 
charged in a letter to the commerce department 
democrats and other advocates for minorities see the refusal to 
adjust as a method of disenfranchising their voters 
new york city mayor david dinkins charged that the undercount of 
minorities will cost cities hundreds of millions of dollars and 
many seats in congress 
they have gotten away with statistical malfeasance for 200 
years and figure they can get away with it for another 10 
dinkins said 
a decision against adjustment is a decision against a more 
accurate census javier p guajardo an assistant attorney 
general in texas wrote the commerce department 
a decision against a more accurate census is a decision 
against fair representation of the american public in particular 
those who need to be counted most minorities the poor and the 
homeless 
the sides already are staking out their positions in terms of 
language with opponents referring to adjustment as fiddling 
with the numbers while those in favor prefer the term 
correcting the count 
rep thomas c sawyer dohio who heads the house subcommittee 
that supervises the census seems to be leaning toward the idea of 
adjustment 
when the billions are spent and the counting is all done will 
we know how many americans there are he was asked 
i hope so when we add in the known error sawyer said 
the question is will we take that into account 
the time he said may have come when the nation is just too 
large for current methods of counting 
we may be seeing the point where we need to consider more 
modern statistical methods to bring the basic numbers closer to the 
truth 
why adjust the census 
because it isnt perfect 
the bureau has never claimed it could count everyone 
in 1980 a bureau analysis estimated that 14 percent of the 
population was missed but the error wasnt uniform 
most white middleclass folks got counted while the poor and 
minorities were more likely to be missed young black men were 
undercounted by as much as 6 percent officials have estimated 
a decade ago the decision on adjustment was left to the census 
bureau statisticians there decided they werent confident enough 
in their methods to make changes in the final numbers 
by 1987 many census workers thought an adjustment could and 
should be made in 1990 
the commerce department stepped in and in late 1987 ruled that 
no adjustment would be made in 1990 the ruling cited statistical 
questions and contended that adjustment would erode confidence in 
the census 
barbara bailar who headed the census office studying 
adjustment resigned 
some politicians and officials charged the decision was 
political because the minorities who are undercounted are more 
likely to be democrats 
a group of local governments led by new york city filed suit 
that suit was settled with a promise by the commerce department 
to reconsider but was later reinstated 
the commerce department has set a group of criteria that will be 
used to make a decision by july 15 1991 several months after the 
numbers have to be delivered to state and local governments for 
reapportionment 
those criteria opponents argued in reinstating their lawsuit 
are so stringent that they virtually prohibit adjustment 
if a decision is eventually made to adjust it will not be until 
mid1991 
because the first census reports will come out dec 31 that 
means there would be two sets of numbers providing easily 
identifiable winners and losers 
the fact that there is a limited amount of money and only 435 
seats in the house of representatives means that every gain by one 
state requires a loss by another 
while the 1990 census will likely mean movement of a dozen or so 
house seats from one state to another the difference between raw 
and adjusted numbers should affect only two to four seats sawyer 
said 
it will also mean a difference of billions of dollars in federal 
and state money distributed over the next 10 years based on 
population numbers 
university of wisconsin historian margo anderson author of a 
book on the history of the census said the framers of the 
constitution knew that the orderly transfer of political 
representation is always disruptive to some groups or interests in 
society 
the test of the new methods is not whether they are 
disruptive but whether they are fair she said adding that the 
departments guidelines for adjustment conjure up an idealized 
history the notion of a 200year process of enumeration which 
cannot be tampered with 
in fact she noted census methods have changed radically over 
the centuries 
the premise that the actual enumeration is the best count 
possible has no factual support john w tukey of princeton 
university told the department 
the census bureau launched its effort to count the estimated 250 
million americans in late march a project expected to take the 
rest of the year 
the tally was embroiled in controversy from the start with 
millions of forms misaddressed 
the public response was less than the bureau had hoped the 
effort has moved to a doortodoor count but that will cost 
considerably more than if people had all received their forms and 
mailed them back 
</TEXT>
