<TEXT>
flight attendants are asking federal 
authorities to give them more protection against the daytoday 
hazards of working on airliners 
cosmic radiation air pollution jet engine noise tobacco 
smoke long working hours and unwieldy beverage carts all pose 
hazards to airliner crews the association of flight attendants 
said in a formal petition tuesday 
the 30000member union asked the federal aviation 
administration to adopt the same standards that protect most other 
workers under the occupational safety and health act 
they really only care about our safety when it comes to 
keeping us alive in a crash so the passengers can be evacuated 
said matthew finucane the unions director of air safety and 
health 
the union accused the faa of preempting osha from protecting 
the aviation work place but of failing itself to guard flight 
attendants and other crew members against disease and injury in the 
sky 
faa spokesman bob buckhorn said the agency had received the 
petition and would review it 
we feel our cabin safety program is very successful said 
buckhorn he said improvements have been made to reduce noise 
levels set flammability standards and install smoke detectors and 
changes are being worked out in duty hour requirements 
buckhorn said seminars are planned to assess and deal with the 
radiation hazard 
a transportation department study in february estimated that 
cosmic radiation could cause one cancer death among 100 crew 
members flying for 20 years airliner occupants are exposed to 
higher radiation from space because there is less atmosphere to 
shield them 
the faa has drafted a circular warning of possible radiation 
danger to crew members who fly long highaltitude routes 
repeatedly over a long period 
the flight attendants petition says poorly designed beverage 
and food carts weighing 200 pounds or more cause about one injury a 
day on us flights 
it says some flight attendants suffer from carpal tunnel 
syndrome which spokesman finucane described as a wrist ailment 
caused by repeatedly subjecting the wrist to awkward positions and 
stress 
finucane said the union has no readily available data on how 
many flight attendants have suffered disease or injury 
crew members are denied certain rights that are guaranteed 
workers in other workplaces union president susan bianchisand 
said in a letter to faa administrator james busey 
it is important not to ignore daytoday occupational health 
and safety issues since cancer can kill as well as crashes said 
ms bianchisand 
the faa deals extensively with aviation safety but has no office 
to oversee crew health she said buckhorn said both passenger and 
crew health issues are handled by cabin safety experts 
the aflcio has called for broader osha protections to include 
transportation workers state and local government employees and 
agricultural workers not covered by the 20yearold act 
