<TEXT>
president bush appears to have concluded that 
economycrippling budget cuts pose a greater political threat to 
republicans than a broken no new taxes campaign promise 
bush has changed positions over the years or at least shown 
flexibility on a range of topics from abortion rights to 
arms control to dealing with soviet president mikhail s gorbachev 
to global warming 
however few pledges have been etched as keenly in recent 
political consciousness as bushs 1988 read my lips no new 
taxes assertion and even as recently as last month bush was 
telling republican audiences he would resist democratic efforts to 
raise taxes 
republican candidates clearly are squirming over the notion of 
tax increases in an election year im not going to vote for 
anything which causes us to lose politically said assistant 
house republican leader newt gingrich of georgia 
but white house strategists apparently decided that the economic 
fallout from massive budget cuts resulting from a failure to 
reach a budget compromise could be an even bigger political 
liability 
so having first put democrats in a box by continually accusing 
them of seeking to raise taxes bush had little choice but to take 
the initiative on tax increases himself 
he did that this week with his no preconditions budget talks 
overture to congress followed by sessions with lawmakers that 
included the first serious exploration of tax options in his 
presidency 
at the same time budget director richard darman was dispatched 
to capitol hill to deliver bad news 
a sluggish economy and previous underestimates of the cost of 
the savings and loan bailout will mean the government may miss 
deficit targets by 60 billion to 100 billion this fall darman 
told lawmakers on tuesday 
although darman suggested that a 100 billion shortfall was an 
extreme case the underlying message was clear 
few close to the budget process in washington have any illusions 
that 60 billion to 100 billion can be whacked from the budget 
through belttightening alone 
and yet if some mix of spending cuts and higher taxes cant be 
assembled and enacted acrosstheboard spending cuts in defense 
and most domestic programs will take place on oct 1 thats the 
start of the new fiscal year and just a month before 1990 
congressional elections 
although some programs would be exempt such as social security 
benefits and interest payments on the national debt the impact of 
such cuts throughout the government could have a crippling effect 
on an already fragile economy 
darman has estimated that cuts of over 20 percent could result 
by contrast when acrosstheboard cuts took effect last year when 
congress failed to meet deficit targets the cuts amounted to less 
than 5 percent 
the grammrudman budget balancing law requires the federal 
deficit now expected to swell to near 200 billion this year to 
be reduced to 100 billion during the current fiscal year and to 
64 billion by next year 
the white house after opening the door to tax increases is now 
trying to close it just enough to minimize political damage 
thus darman said that while bush is open to discuss any 
proposal there are some ideas were not prepared to put on the 
table 
however democratic leaders are suggesting that the president 
had better spell out just what kind of taxes he can support if he 
expects to win their cooperation in forging a serious bipartisan 
compromise 
budget summits between the white house and congress have taken 
place before but they have produced few concrete results 
this year may be different because of the seriousness with which 
bush is approaching the issue and the magnitude of the deficit 
problem suggests former rep thomas ashley dohio 
i think there is a greater prospect of deliverability on both 
sides this year ashley said last year i dont think either 
the white house or congress was in a position to attack the 
politically sensitive issues 
ashley a former member of the house budget committee who speaks 
regularly with bush said deficit cuts such as those required this 
year cannot be achieved without new taxes 
is bush really ready to abandon his campaign pledge and support 
some form of tax increase ashley said yes 
one thing is clear the white house is not saying everything 
is on the table because it has a ring to it they have to be 
willing to deal he said 
</TEXT>
