the phoenix fiber cookie that promises weight 
loss and protection from cancer and other diseases is being removed 
from store shelves under threat of court action by federal 
regulators 
lawyers for phoenix international marketing corp of sparks 
nev said after meeting with food and drug administration 
officials tuesday that the cookie would be recalled and 
distribution of related products halted 
the company is cooperating fully with the fda its pulling 
back all the objectionable promotional material and they hope to 
come out with a new product shortly said david weeda a 
washingtonbased lawyer for the company 
the fda last friday told the company to take the products off 
the market because promotional materials for them made 
unsubstantiated medical claims the agency threatened to go to 
court if the company did not comply 
the material distributed about the phoenix for life weight 
control program claimed the products were useful in weight control 
and in maintaining cardiovascular health could prevent colon 
cancer and could help people with diabetes forgo medication the 
agency said 
the fda also said the cookies contained twice the approximately 
120 calories claimed on the label and disguised sugar content by 
saying on the label that the cookies contained 100 percent 
natural cane juice 
the company plans to change the recipe for the cookie and draft 
new labeling if the new labeling is approved by the fda a new 
product could be on the market within a month weeda said 
phoenix also is discontinuing temporarily other products in its 
diet plan phoenix fizzie which dissolves in water to make a 
lemonflavored drink phoenix nutritious beverage and phoenix 
vitamins and minerals capsules 
whether these products will be reintroduced is up in the 
air weeda said 
referring to the fdas charges another company attorney dennis 
johnson said were not contesting fdas conclusions 
the phoenix fiber cookie represents more than 90 percent of the 
companys sales which have soared this year from 2 million in 
january to 4 million in february and 10 million in march 
johnson said 
the cookie introduced less than two years ago contains large 
amounts of fiber and comes in chocolate chip oatmeal raisin and 
vanilla 
as part of the phoenix weightcontrol program limiting calories 
to 1200 to 1500 per day the company recommends eating a cookie 
and drinking two glasses of water in place of a meal 
the company has hired a nutritionist to review its diet plan and 
suggest changes weeda said 
