<TEXT>
finance ministers from 152 nations are heading 
home after stopping short of endorsing a 13 billion fund to help 
eastern european and third world countries protect the environment 
france supported the establishment of the green fund but 
the united states and other powerful members of the international 
monetary fund and its sister organization the world bank balked 
britain and japan also opposed the new program which was backed 
by world bank president barber conable 
the world bank already keeps environmental considerations in 
mind when lending for development projects and it supports some 
environmental projects in poor countries but conable argued that a 
new program was needed to address pollution problems that spill 
across borders 
the proposal was debated into the evening tuesday by the 
22member development committee a joint body of the imf and world 
bank that sets policy for the agencies development lending 
in a statement the committee said further work was 
necessary on the proposal and that meantime the world bank 
should take steps to reinforce its existing environmental 
programs 
french finance minister pierre beregovoy had pleaded with other 
countries to send a positive signal by approving the program 
now time is passing he said 
among the projects that would be eligible are those aimed at 
protecting the ozone layer promoting diversity of animal and plant 
species reducing emission of gases thought to cause global 
warming protecting multinational river systems and preventing 
deforestation and the spread of deserts 
the idea is that no matter how zealous industrialized countries 
are in attacking those problems within their boundaries the 
problems will not improve unless underdeveloped nations also 
participate 
there is no doubt industrial countries are under the 
obligation to avoid deterioration of the environment 
beregovoy said developing countries must also mobilize and 
we must help them to do so 
the green fund as envisioned by conable would be a pilot 
project lending 13 billion over for three years at low interest 
rates 
much of the money would go to third world nations but eastern 
european countries that had neglected their environment under four 
decades of communist rule would also be eligible 
however the united states concerned about its budget deficit 
and other large contributors to the world bank argued the agency 
should work to strengthen its existing environmental programs 
it should for instance play a greater role in promoting 
debtfornature swaps in which a developing country agrees to 
preserve its rain forest for instance in exchange for a reduction 
in its debt burden treasury secretary nicholas brady said 
