<TEXT>
public schools are failing to deal effectively 
with emotionally disabled children and at least twothirds of all 
such youngsters arent getting any help at all a 
soontobepublished study says 
schools tend to emphasize silence and obedience over learning 
and offer few opportunities for the emotionally handicapped to work 
with other children or learn social skills according to the study 
by researchers at bank street college of education in new york 
many other youngters are being mislabeled as emotionally 
disabled simply because they are mad bad sad and cant add 
and have thus gotten on the nerves of their teachers the study 
found 
some 400000 students less than 1 percent of the school 
population have been identified as having behavior disorders by 
school authorities but studies estimate the true proportion is at 
least three to five times higher 
this suggests that at best somewhere between 10 and 30 percent 
of children in need are identified said the report 
youngsters with behavioral handicaps are entitled to special 
education under federal law but whether or not emotionally 
handicapped children get special help from their schools depends as 
much on available resources and local attitudes toward difficult 
behavior as on students needs the report said 
the report also found that only one out of three emotionally 
disabled students functions at or above grade level and 42 percent 
drop out 
the study to be published later this month was written by jane 
knitzer zina steinberg and brahm fleisch 
it was based on questionnaires sent to state directors of 
special education and mental health officials visits to 26 
programs in 13 states a review of literature in the field and 
interviews with parents and educators from 1987 to 1989 
the report leaves me optimistic simply because such a report 
finally exists said william schipper executive director of the 
national association of state directors of special education 
this is a very tough group to educate a highcost group but 
the state of practice is well well behind what the research tells 
us he said 
the report singled out a few exemplary programs 
golden lake elementary in circle pine minn sends special 
educators into regular classrooms allowing youngsters to stay with 
normal peers 
central park east school in harlem and elementary schools in new 
haven conn benton harbor mich and prince georges county 
md have begun reforms that help all students such schools tend 
to shy from labeling youngsters handicapped 
states for their part need to reexamine policies the report 
said in some states for example school districts are off the 
hook financially if a student is referred to a state facility 
</TEXT>
