<TEXT>
the national institutes of health has reprimanded 
childrens hospital for failing to seek parents consent for a 
comparison study of two treatments for infants with damaged lungs 
the hospital made a serious error in not asking for consent 
from the parents of babies chosen randomly to receive conventional 
treatment the federal agency said in a recent letter quoted in 
todays the boston globe 
nineteen of the 20 babies who received the experimental 
treatment survived against six of 10 treated conventionally 
the tests were part of a study that was published in december 
and confirmed the value of the experimental treatment 
extracorporeal membrane oxygenation or ecmo which breathes 
for the infants until their lungs can take over 
charles r mccarthy director of the nih office for protection 
from research risks said the committee at childrens hospital that 
approves all human studies made decisions that rightfully belong 
to the parents they really blew it 
the action is believed to be the only time the federal office 
has reprimanded a hospital for failing to ask consent of all 
subjects in a study 
dr peter h wolff of childrens hospital told the agency in a 
letter that he would seek consent in all future human studies 
but wolff chairman of the committee that approves human studies 
at the hospital defended the failure to seek consent saying that 
asking all parents for permission would impose unacceptable 
psychological burdens on the parents of children not included in 
the ecmo arm of the study 
dr michael epstein who led the study said that parents of 
conventionally treated infants were not informed to spare them 
anguish he said that even if they decided not to allow their child 
to participate there was no way they could have obtained the 
experimental treatment for their child at least not at childrens 
i continue to be troubled by all of this discussion he 
said but i still feel that we acted in a morally appropriate 
way given the conditions at the time 
at the time the experimental treatment was available at many 
other us hospitals and some studies indicated it offered better 
chances of survival to infants with severely damaged lungs 
however no random controlled study had proven its advantage or 
documented its safety 
wolffs committee decided not to seek consent of all 
participants to avoid difficulty recruiting subjects for the 
conventional treatment according to a letter from mccarthys 
office sent to the hospital in november 
the hospital researchers have acknowledged in scientific reports 
that a random study would probably show large differences in 
survival between emco and the standard therapy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

