<TEXT>
a german observatory known as rosat 
will be carried into orbit aboard a delta rocket may 31 to study 
the heavens for sources of cosmic xrays 
the 170 million satellite will perform the first full sky 
survey of celestial bodies that emit xrays said volker 
kaltenbach rosat spacecraft manager for the german aerospace 
research establishment of west germany 
it will use the largest imaging xray telescope ever built 
rosat is up to now the most ambitious project in the young 
history of xray astronomy kaltenbach said tuesday 
about 1000 sources of cosmic xrays which do not penetrate the 
atmosphere and therefore are invisible from the ground are known 
to exist 
astronomers hope rosat will identify 100000 sources said alan 
bunner rosat program scientist for nasa it will observe stars 
black holes and supernova remnants hot clouds produced by 
exploding stars at the end of their lives 
the observatory originally was scheduled to be carried into 
orbit by a space shuttle but the 1986 challenger explosion delayed 
the mission along with everything else and neither the german 
aerospace research establishment nor nasa wanted to wait until the 
mid1990s bunner said 
rosat was redesigned somewhat to be launched aboard mcdonnell 
douglas unmanned delta 2 rocket from cape canaveral air force 
station bunner said 
the 170 million cost of the satellite excludes rocket and 
launch expenses which are being covered by nasa the united states 
has contributed about 106 million to the project great britain 
also has paid part of the costs 
rosat is short for roentgen satellite named after german 
scientist wilhelm conrad rontgen who discovered xrays in 1895 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

