<TEXT>
drought is forcing part of the san 
francisco bay area to ration water for the second time in three 
years 
under the plan approved tuesday by the city public utilities 
commission the cost of water will jump beginning in july by 
about 9 percent increasing the average household bill to 628 a 
month 
water customers will be given allotments based on the number of 
people in a household those who use 10 percent above the allotment 
will have their base rate doubled while big water wasters may face 
a tenfold rate increase 
in addition hosing down sidewalks is forbidden decorative 
water fountains will be shut off and restaurant customers will not 
be given water unless they ask for it 
there is a real emergency said rodel rodis commission 
president 
officials aim to cut consumption to 25 percent of 1987 levels 
for a total of 22 million people about a third of the bay area 
population in san francisco san mateo and santa clara counties 
and alameda county across the san francisco bay 
it is the fourth straight year of drought in northern 
california rationing also was ordered in 1988 before that it was 
last rationed in 1977 
in march the santa clara valley water district in the southern 
part of the san francisco bay area ordered mandatory cuts of 20 
percent to 25 percent 
some parched southern california communities also are rationing 
water 
