<TEXT>
president bush looking for an agreement to highlight his 
upcoming summit is offering to halt production of chemical weapons 
if the soviets set a schedule for destroying their poison gas 
stockpiles administration officials said today 
with the visit of mikhail s gorbachev less than two weeks away 
and other arms control negotiations running into snags bush would 
like to conclude a chemical weapons agreement 
however the officials who spoke on condition of anonymity 
said the soviets had to meet two conditions before the united 
states would agree to stop turning out chemical weapons 
the first they said is to agree to a schedule to destroy the 
soviet stockpiles the other is to allow the united states to keep 
a small arsenal until all nations capable of production agree to a 
global accord 
initially bush last year offered to end production over eight 
years but now the officials said he is willing to set a date far 
short of that if the soviets meet the conditions 
secretary of state james a baker iii will explore prospects 
when he meets in moscow next week with soviet foreign minister 
eduard a shevardnadze 
they are also to go over problems in other arms control fields 
the most difficult concern a proposed treaty to cut longrange 
nuclear missiles bombers and submarines by up to 50 percent on 
each side 
bush and gorbachev had hoped to sign such a treaty at their may 
30june 3 summit here but as the date draws close many 
differences remain these include a soviet demand to restrict 
multiwarhead missiles carried on warships the administration is 
resisting this and also insisting on retaining more airlaunched 
cruise missiles than the soviets have proposed 
a chemical weapons agreement at the summit would be historic and 
serve the political purpse of distracting attention from slow 
progress in other areas 
the united states now has about 32000 tons of poison gas us 
officials consider the soviet stockpile to be somewhat larger even 
though moscow announced in 1987 that it had stopped production 
