<TEXT>
bicyclists would be required to wear 
helmets under legislation passed by a maryland county council a 
law one safety expert said would be watched nationwide 
the legislation which goes into effect 150 days after it is 
signed by howard county executive elizabeth bobo would be the 
nations toughest helmet law howard county lies between baltimore 
and washington dc and has a population of 180000 
the county council approved the legislation 32 monday night 
bobo has indicated she will sign the legislation within the next 10 
days 
new york and california have limited helmet laws for children 
under 5 
the legislation should create a ripple effect nationally 
said dr andrew dannenberg of the johns hopkins injury prevention 
center 
andy clarke of the bicycle federation of america who had 
expressed concerns about the legislation at a public hearing 
agreed that passage of the bill will have a national impact for 
sure many jurisdictions will be watching to see if it works 
firsttime violators would be subjected to fines of up to 50 a 
second violation would carry a 100 fine if it occurred within 12 
months of the first but a judge could waive the fine if a cyclist 
showed proof of having purchased a helmet 
dannenberg said he will lobby for similar legislation on a state 
or national level 
i will also try to get support for having helmets included in 
the price of bicycles to increase the accessibility of helmets 
said dannenberg whose center will be monitoring the use of helmets 
in the county under the legislation 
the deaths of three youths in bicycle accidents in western 
howard county during the past three years prompted county 
councilman charles c feaga to introduce the bill 
clarkes organization had expressed doubt about whether the law 
would be accepted by the public he had said a major bikesafety 
education effort should be tried first 
about 600 children die each year nationwide in bicycle 
accidents and head injuries are the most common cause of death 
said fred rivara director of the harbor view injury prevention 
center in seattle 
rivara said a study by the seattle center showed that helmets 
would prevent 88 percent of the brain injuries suffered by cyclists 
helmets usually cost about 50 but rivara said some 
jurisdictions have gotten discounts from manufacturers that brought 
the cost down to as low as 20 
