nasa engineers delayed until at least friday 
an attempt to snap the first photograph of stars using the main 
camera of the hubble space telescope the space agency said today 
nasa had said tuesday that they would try to get the first 
picture today even if engineers had to interrupt the telescopes 
shakedown tests now entering the third week 
but nasa spokesman dave garrett said today the first light 
picture will not be until at least friday 
garrett said he had no information about the reason for the 
delay other public affairs officers more closely connected to the 
hubble program were not available 
the first light picture is the traditional first photograph of 
the stars taken by a new telescope 
the plan would be to photograph a 3 billionyearold star field 
called theta carina or the ships keel visible in the 
southern sky the star cluster 1260 light years away can be seen 
with the naked eye from parts of africa south america and 
australia 
on tuesday ground controllers tried unsuccessfully to teach the 
telescope exactly what in the heavens it is looking at the 
instrument was told to look for stars of a certain brightness in 
what scientists thought was a rich field it found none 
it was somewhat of a surprise said michael harrington the 
nasa manager in charge of the checkout we had expected that this 
field has a plenitude of that size stars and that we had no problem 
getting plenty it didnt turn out quite like that 
once the telescope locks on to the bright stars it will 
remember where it was pointing and that in turn will enable it 
later to find any other target ordered by the ground 
the sequence is like looking at a map to determine your location 
and then being able to go to any point from there 
harrington said there probably were gaps in the star field 
without any stars of the brightness being sought we thought we 
had hit the field that was rich enough its not a problem with the 
instrument 
the 125ton telescope which cost 15 billion was released 
from the space shuttle discovery on april 25 before tuesdays 
failed effort engineers estimated they were one week behind 
schedule in their checkout because of earlier problems 
the telescopes mission is to collect the light generated by 
galaxies and other heavenly bodies billions of years ago it will 
enable astronomers to look far deeper into the universe than 
possible with groundbased telescopes 
teams of engineers are concentrating on two persistent problems 
on the telescope one is a jittery action when the instrument is 
instructed to roll the other is a shaking motion when the 
telescope passes from shadow into sunlight as it orbits the earth 
