<DOCNO> AP900509-0095 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
two new reports conclude that the experimental 
drug ddi is a promising weapon against aids but a top government 
researcher cautions doctors and patients to suspend judgment 
until much larger studies are finished 
the latest work found that the medicine improved aids patients 
blood counts increased their energy and helped them put on weight 
but it also shows that the treatment can cause severe even 
lifethreatening side effects 
there is some evidence that it inhibits the aids virus said 
dr howard a liebman of boston city hospital the important 
question is will the spectrum of toxicity prove to be the limiting 
factor of the drug will that make it not any better than azt and 
perhaps worse 
doctors hope that and other questions about ddi will be answered 
by a major new study under way at hospitals across the united 
states 
the two newly published studies were conducted on small numbers 
of patients by doctors at boston city hospital and the university 
of rochester the results published in thursdays new england 
journal of medicine were similar to those of a national cancer 
institute preliminary study published last july in the journal 
science 
all three studies were socalled phase i trials they were 
intended to determine the maximum safe dose that patients can 
tolerate not whether the medicine had an effect on their illness 
nevertheless the researchers found that many of the patients 
clearly improved while taking ddi for a few weeks 
in an editorial in the new england journal the director of aids 
work at the national institutes of health wrote that there 
certainly is a suggestion of shortterm benefit from ddi 
currently about 800 patients are enrolled in a study that 
compares ddi to azt or zidovudine the only aids medicine approved 
by the us food and drug administration for routine use an 
additional 8600 people who cannot take azt because of side effects 
or worsening symptoms are using ddi in an unusual program that 
makes the drug available before its formal approval 
in the editorial dr anthony s fauci predicted that the two 
latest reports will stir up inevitable enthusiasm about the 
treatment 
but he added physicians and patients should suspend judgment 
about ddi until the multicenter phase iiiii clinical trials 
currently in progress are completed 
the new england journal studies were directed by drs john s 
lambert of rochester and timothy p cooley of boston city and 
involved 71 patients many of the patients felt better or put on 
weight while taking ddi virus levels fell while the blood cells 
attack by the aids virus increased 
however high doses of the drug also caused inflammation of the 
pancreas and severe foot pain 
liebman who was senior author of the boston city study said 
the potentially fatal pancreatic ailment often occurred after three 
or four months of ddi treatment and frequently affected the sickest 
patients 
physicians have to be very alert to the toxicities he said 
a lot of physicians are not sensitive to this they are just 
happy to be able to give something to their patients 
even if ddi turns out to be no better than azt it still may be 
an alternative drug for some patients azt often loses its 
effectiveness after a year or so of treatment it also suppresses 
the bodys ability to make new blood cells 
also in the journal dutch doctors reported an unsuccessful 
attempt to prevent an accidental aids infection by giving azt the 
victim a patient in the hospital for an intestinal operation was 
mistakenly given an injection with a syringe that contained a small 
amount of aidstainted blood 
doctors quickly recognized their mistake and began giving him 
azt within 45 minutes however the drug failed to stop the virus 
and the man became infected 
azt is routinely recommended to prevent infections in hospital 
workers who accidentally jab themselves with needles that have been 
used on aids patients the report written by dr joep ma lange 
and others from the university of amsterdam shows that the 
strategy may not always work 
</TEXT>
