<TEXT>
cockroaches centipedes and crabs are 
skittering on teensyweensy treadmills to help scientists learn 
more about how the little critters get from here to there 
so far biologist robert fulls research team has found that 
insects run rather than walk and that cockroaches beetles dogs 
and humans all use the same basic gait when they run 
crabs however gallop 
fulls laboratory at the university of california berkeley 
contains a series of miniature treadmills in airtight plastic 
boxes air tubes connected to the boxes allow full and his students 
to measure ittybitty amounts of oxygen consumed by jogging 
cockroaches 
the scientists also can measure the force exerted by insects 
individual footfalls 
each insect or crab is put through its paces for 10 to 15 
minutes at a time in a series of tests lasting a couple of weeks 
full found the amount of energy a creature uses getting from one 
place to another has nothing to do with how many legs it has or 
even how smoothly it runs or walks 
instead energy expenditure depends on the amount of force 
produced by leg muscles and the amount of time it takes each leg to 
go through a whole cycle of movement 
this seems to be true all the way from an awkward marathon 
winner to a centipede weaving over the ground full said 
researchers also learned that the energy required to walk or run 
depends largely on the force needed to hold the body up against 
gravity and not so much on mechanical power needed to swing the 
legs and propel the body forward 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900509-0108 </DOCNO>
