<TEXT>
an advocacy group recommended wednesday that 
person who stay home to care for children or disabled family 
members be given social security credit 
the older womens league said current law penalizes women who 
are more likely than men to leave the work force for family duties 
that give them no credit in the social security system 
the group released a report that executive director joan 
kuriansky said shows in brutal detail what is in store for 
americas midlife and younger women 
the report said that federal pension policies mean unmarried and 
widowed women who retire 30 years from now are much more likely to 
live in poverty than either married women or men 
at fault the report said are social security and private 
pension systems that favor the traditional family and so 
benefit men owl said fewer than 10 percent of american families 
fit the traditional profile of a working father homemaker mother 
and two children 
there are systemwide inequities that will continue to 
penalize women owl president lou glasse said at a news 
conference where release of the report was timed to precede 
mothers day this sunday 
pension eligibility has generally required longterm 
continuous fulltime service with one employer a bad fit for 
women she said 
glasse said congress should at least allow debate on the idea of 
social security credit for nonworking caregivers 
policy makers should realize that women do move in and out of 
the workforce kuriansky said 
owl also called on congress to 
mandate portable pension plans so that people who change jobs 
may take with them all retirement contributions 
reduce from five the maximum number of years employers may 
require for vesting 
owl claimed that for most women decades of social security 
contributions will translate into virtually the same retirement 
benefits as those paid to their mothers who may never have earned 
wages or paid social security taxes 
the league said that 20 years into the next century social 
security and private pension plans will have practically ended 
poverty among older men and couples but financial problems will 
remain widespread for single women 
glasse said women 30 years away from retirement are already in 
jeopardy 
the report said the 55yearold social security system and 
private pension plans penalize women who typically live longer 
than men but earn less money the owl said 70 percent of baby boom 
women will outlive their husbands by about 15 years but on 
average will earn about twothirds the pay for men their age 
if our nations social security and pension programs remain 
fundamentally unchanged the retirement income future is unlikely 
to get any brighter for women the league said 
