<TEXT>
it is 2 oclock on a thursday somewhere in the 
lush and leafy suburbs a bell rings a woman opens a book and 
reads aloud the treasured words of herman melvilles moby dick 
while 21 women listen in rapture 
welcome to the thursday club where great books have been read 
aloud every week for 100 years and while most of its members are 
elderly the club and others like it are thriving 
no one knows how many americans belong to such clubs which can 
trace their origins to before the civil war when housewives found a 
way to awaken sleeping intellects but according to bowdoin college 
professor theodora penny martin the impulse persists 
ms martin gets a glimpse of this whenever she gives a talk 
about her 1987 book on the early days of womens reading clubs 
the sound of our own voices 
women of middle age and even younger the minute they hear 
about the clubs want to tell me about a book club they are in 
ms martin said in a telephone interview from brunswick maine 
there still is that sense of wanting to be intellectually 
alive outside their jobs and also a sense of wanting to be part of 
a circle of women she said 
the thursday club with two members in their 90s and most in 
their 60s and 70s is still the exclusive invitationonly group it 
was in 1890 
members still take turns being hostesses of readings every 
thursday from 2 pm to 4 pm october to may the routine 
strictly kept is one hour of reading from a book of lasting value 
such as works by james joyce charles dickens homer goethe and 
confucius they also read more contemporary writers such as james 
baldwin gabriel garcia marquez alice walker and thomas mann 
a brief break follows with water the sole refreshment then 
comes an hour of lighter fare such as poetry or plays 
i feel as though i am witnessing the last members of a very 
special generation raised by victorian grandmothers i dont 
think there are women who are like this anywhere its a rarefied 
little group said deborah youngman 
at 39 ms youngman is the baby as one member described the 
doctoral candidate in human development 
i imagined it would be the quintessential bluestocking affair 
it was not i also assumed it would be a marvelous opportunity to 
observe local high quaint said the native californian now living 
in belmont 
i couldnt have been more naive they are rather more than 
middleaged rather more than middleclass white clad in good old 
wool and sensible shoes theyre very very serious 
they are rich and evocative but not in cakes and tea ms 
youngman said 
such reading clubs began in the midwest in 1860 and reached 
their heyday around 1900 when membership was estimated at nearly 1 
million typically comprising welloff housewives with children in 
school and servants at home 
for a long time the literary gatherings provided women unable 
to attend college a place to use their minds but early in this 
century women were finally getting into many schools and reading 
clubs began to fall by the way 
the clubs also felt the drain and distraction of women during 
the two world wars further decimation occurred after the 1960s as 
the women who might have joined reading clubs poured into 
universities and out again into professions 
groups like the thursday club may one day vanish ms youngman 
said she fears that one day she will be its last member and the one 
to take its archives to their final rest at the belmont public 
library 
she should talk to alfreda l irwin 
mrs irwin 77 an author and journalist is now in chautauqua 
ny but she still belongs to the wednesday club she joined as a 
housewife in 1938 in franklin pa 
i go back and its just marvelous because they have all these 
wonderful educated women who are just very anxious to participate 
in this interesting club she said in a telephone interview 
</TEXT>
