the heralddispatch huntington wva on defense spending 
reality is beginning to soak in at the pentagon if defense 
secretary dick cheneys proposals for cutting advanced aircraft 
spending is any indication 
still it wouldnt be very difficult for someone such as say 
sen sam nunn dga chairman of the senate armed services 
committee to find far deeper cuts that could be made in the 
defense budget 
though cheney has proposed cuts of about 35 billion between 
1991 and 1997 that amounts to less than 2 percent of the original 
figure about 2 trillion that the armchair generals and 
admirals at the pentagon had anticipated spending during that 
period 
congress could and should demand far larger cuts 
the cold war is over the berlin wall is no more eastern europe 
has rejected communism the warsaw pact is falling apart and the 
soviet union itself is undergoing unprecedented internal turmoil 
yet the soviet union remains a nuclear superpower and yes 
the united states must continue to maintain a strong defense 
keeping our guard up against any eventuality nonetheless the 
current course of events should make it clear that this country can 
make far deeper spending cuts at the pentagon than cheney proposes 
every unnecessary defense dollar that is cut can add to 
americas economic strength and as the 1990s unfold that strength 
will perhaps mean far more to our national security than more 
tanks bombers and nuclear missiles 
