<TEXT>
the number of deer to be hunted in northern 
wisconsin each year should be equally divided between the chippewa 
tribe and nonindians a federal judge ruled wednesday 
us district judge barbara crabb said equal division between 
the states six chippewa bands and nonindian hunters should assure 
enough deer for both parties 
crabbs ruling came in a lawsuit filed by the chippewa her 
decision to limit tribal deer hunting to 50 percent of the 
available resource contrasts sharply with her earlier ruling that 
the chippewa should be entitled to 100 percent of the safe 
allowable catch of fish in northern wisconsin 
crabb refused to discuss why her deer decision differed from the 
one on fish catch 
wisconsins six chippewa bands retain the right to spearfish 
hunt and cut timber offreservation on public lands in northern 
wisconsin under 19thcentury federal treaties 
since a court affirmed those rights in 1983 the chippewa have 
exercised their spearfishing rights on northern lakes encountering 
huge and sometimes violent protests by outdoorsmen 
the opponents argue that the special treaty rights are unfair 
because they are denied to nonindians 
since the court ruling affirming the rights the chippewa bands 
have filed a series of lawsuits asking the court to define how much 
of the resources of northern wisconsin they are entitled to under 
the treaties and to what degree the state can regulate tribal 
activities 
crabb previously ruled the indians are entitled to 100 percent 
of the safe harvest of walleye on northern lakes during 
spearfishing safe refers to the number of fish biologists say can 
be taken without harming fish populations she has yet to rule on 
how much timber the tribe should be allowed to cut 
