<TEXT>
the budget adviser to congress said wednesday 
the federal gasoline tax may be used for purposes other than 
building highways and bridges 
there is no fundamental economic or governmental reason for 
earmarking tax revenues for specific purposes w david 
montgomery of the congressional budget office told a senate 
transportation subcommittee 
montgomery also said the activities of the highway trust fund 
should not be split off from the rest of the budget 
taking the fund offbudget would make the budget a less 
precise indicator of fiscal policy he said finally the 
existence of the fund and the presence of cash balances can lead to 
pressures for spending that impede deficit reduction and distort 
budget priorities 
the bush administration has also testified through the 
transportation department that the activities of the multibillion 
dollar fund should not be set apart from the rest of the budget 
montgomerys testimony to the senate environment and public 
works subcommittee on water resources transportation and 
infrastructure came in the second day of hearings on the use of the 
governments highway and aviation funds 
a house public works and transportation subcommittee heard 
testimony tuesday 
the two transportation funds are financed through fuel and 
ticket taxes and other user fees the proceeds are supposed to be 
spent on highways bridges and air traffic improvements a small 
share goes to mass transportation 
the funds have accumulated a 25 billion cash balance over the 
years but the real surplus is in dispute because large sums of the 
highway portion are committed to future spending by states 
a custody battle has developed over those funds between the 
states construction industry rural lawmakers and congressional 
public works committees on one side and the tax and 
budgetwriting committees of congress and urban lawmakers on the 
other 
money that goes out of the funds to repair crumbling bridges and 
highways raises the overall deficit unless revenues increase 
correspondingly 
wednesdays hearing was prompted by legislation by sen richard 
bryan dnev that would force the government to release 9 
billion in supposedly unspent trust fund dollars over the next 
three years 
in the house rep bob mcewen rohio has introduced 
legislation that would take the highway fund off budget 
