<TEXT>
nato defense ministers wednesday 
opened their first nuclear strategy session since upheavals in 
eastern europe caused the unraveling of the sovietled warsaw pact 
the officials of the north atlantic treaty organization gathered 
for two days of talks in the rugged kananaskis region of the 
canadian rocky mountains site of the 1988 winter olympic games 
the ministers are under pressure to redo their nuclear policy in 
response to greatly reduced eastwest tensions 
west german officials said defense minister gerhard stoltenberg 
intended to press his counterparts to withdraw quickly all of 
natos nuclear artillery shells most of which are deployed in west 
germany 
stoltenberg told reporters earlier this week that it was 
possible for all landbased nuclear systems to be removed from 
europe 
but he linked the withdrawals to a soviet willingness to do the 
same it cannot be unilateral he said it must be on both 
sides 
any push for a quick onesided pullout of nuclear weapons from 
europe would likely be opposed by both the united states and 
britain 
british officials said they do not favor the socalled third 
zero military jargon for the elimination of landbased 
shortrange nuclear missiles in europe 
discussions about scaling back the wests arsenal of battlefield 
nuclear weapons were given fresh impetus last week by president 
bush he announced the cancellation of plans to build a more 
powerful version of the lance shortrange missile and a modernized 
155mm nucleartipped artillery shell 
tactical weapons most deployed in west germany can only hit 
targets in the now friendly countries of eastern europe 
as nato reduces its landbased forces analysts expect it to put 
more emphasis on airlaunched nuclear systems the united states is 
developing a tactical airtosurface missile known as the tasm 
which would replace gravity bombs 
american and british officials though seem intent on avoiding 
any debate on deployment of the new longerrange missile 
there is a certain feeling not to have the meeting dominated 
by tasm said an official who demanded anonymity 
west germany is thought to be reluctant to get into any 
discussions about stationing the tasm missile on aircraft on its 
soil the bonn government holding sensitive negotiations on its 
merger with east germany is mindful of soviet security concerns 
the west contends it needs nuclear weapons to offset the warsaw 
pacts overwhelming superiority in tanks and other conventional 
arms 
the united states and the soviet union are expected to enter 
into negotiations possibly early next year on cutting shortrange 
systems 
a dutch newspaper het parool reported wednesday that the 
united states plans to site 389 new tasm missiles in seven european 
nato nations starting in 1995 if the alliance approves the program 
the plan provides for tasm sites in west germany britain 
italy turkey the netherlands belgium and greece the newspaper 
did not say how it had obtained the information 
at a summit last may bush and other alliance leaders agreed 
that bargaining on the tactical weapons could not occur until 
implementation of an accord reducing tanks artillery troops and 
other conventional arms in europe 
but bush announced last week an acceleration of the timetable 
saying bargaining could start once agreement was reached 
negotiators of nato and the warsaw pact are pressing for a deal by 
fall 
the meeting of the nuclear planning group is one of a series of 
highlevel nato talks this month and next on the alliances future 
and its need for nuclear and conventional forces 
the discussions will wind up with a summer summit of bush and 
other alliance leaders 
all 16 nato nations except france attend the nuclear meetings 
held twice a year france is a nato member but does not belong to 
the alliances integrated military structure iceland which has no 
armed forces has observer status 
