<TEXT>
at the height of violence that rocked 
south koreas capital wednesday a young woman with a ponytail 
ducked into a doorway with a makeshift medical bag to aid a student 
bleeding from the head 
the thunder of volleys of police tear gas shells shook the 
ground clouds of acrid gas billowed along the street in front of 
her like great balls of fog nearby students gagged or vomited 
the girl carefully wrapped the young mans head with bandages 
and gave him a hug 
moments before the young man had been hurling firebombs at a 
us diplomatic building and yelling yankee go home his 
friends later forced riot policemen to kneel and then they beat 
them 
the two both radical students are among the elite of south 
koreas young those able to gain admittance to universities they 
are the pride of a country that equates education with prosperity 
yet they are a deep embarrassment in a society that values harmony 
most of the radical students claim they are serving their 
country the countrys government says most of them are naive 
leftists who have been brainwashed by communist north korean 
teachings some of them the government has said may be communist 
agents 
who are these students and what do they want 
radicals wear american jeans and sneakers carry their books in 
a backpack and look like college students everywhere they go to 
some of the best schools in south korea 
radical students number only about 5 percent of the roughly 1 
million students in college other students listen to their 
rallies read their newspapers or may agree with some of their 
views but they do not usually participate 
radicals are demanding more democratic reforms from a government 
they claim has been too slow to do so they view the january merger 
of the governing party with two opposition parties as a political 
coup intended to prolong a hold on power without an election 
down with president roh taewoo they shout many feel an 
overthrow of the government could solve the countrys problems but 
offer few details on how a new leader could do better 
radicals claim washington makes decisions for a seoul puppet 
government they demand the withdrawal of 43000 us troops based 
in south korea because they say their presence hinders unification 
talks with north korea 
none of them are old enough to remember the bloody 195053 
korean war launched by north korea the war in which 5 million 
americans served some of them say they have never talked to an 
american 
at protests women collect rocks wave banners tend to injuries 
and sing support songs men deployed in platoon fashion hurl 
firebombs and rocks 
the radical student movement lost momentum after roh took office 
in february 1988 promising broad democratic reforms the smaller 
numbers forced radicals to become more violent to be noticed some 
began to use homemade explosives 
the government privately worries the violent protests could 
breed discontent among older south koreans especially laborers who 
often feel underprivileged and underpaid 
with escalating prices and doubledigit inflation rohs 
government has declined in popularity and its mindful of 
studentworker alliances that have wrought change in the past 
in 1960 hundreds of thousands of students took to the streets 
to demand the fall of president syngman rhee regime in 1987 
hundreds of thousands of students spurred an authoritarian former 
president chun doohwan to make reforms discontented workers 
joined those protests 
in korea protests are a statement the president of a seoul 
university said on condition of anonymity eventually the country 
may mature enough not to have to make the statement with violence 
its embarrassing 
