record floods that are saturating 
hundreds of houses are striking at people who often dont have 
flood insurance a state official says some cant get it some 
cant afford it and some dont bother 
flood insurance is a hot topic while the arkansas river is 
slopped over its banks the river crested tuesday to a record level 
at little rock and was expected reach 48 feet wednesday at pine 
bluff a foot above flood stage 
fa crockett wishes he hadnt let his flood insurance policies 
lapse a few years ago he says he cant recall getting a renewal 
notice for his flood insurance and assumed he no longer needed it 
i went along for years and didnt think nothing about it 
said the 72yearold crockett who owns a used car dealership i 
dont know much about insurance except that i pay the premium 
now water is waist deep or higher in five houses he owns 
statewide about 500 homes are under water between 250 and 300 
of them in jefferson county official said corps of engineers 
spokesman pj spaul put early estimates of flood damage at 15 
million to 20 million statewide 
the damage to agriculture is not yet tallied cattlemen say 
hundreds of cattle have drowned or are trapped by flood waters the 
spring wheat crop is lost in some counties and flooded fields 
further delay spring rice planting 
jefferson county probably will lose onesixth of its 60 million 
annual agricultural sales said frank plafcan of the county 
extension office 
a federal disaster declaration for arkansas flooded counties 
could come later this week civil defense officials said 
in texas where flooding and heavy rains have claimed 12 lives 
in the last two weeks and president bush declared disaster areas in 
16 counties the red cross estimates that 4000 homes have been 
damaged or destroyed by flooding 
