<TEXT>
two auctions of contemporary art featured lower 
prices this week suggesting that the market has stopped its 
frenzied climb upward and buyers are becoming more selective art 
experts said wednesday 
the experts said the contemporary art market is still healthy 
and they did not fear a bust even though many paintings didnt 
sell or sold well below their estimated prices 
people are more than willing to pay top sums for excellent 
pieces of art but are not willing to pay inflated prices for 
secondrate works of art said larry gagosian a madison avenue 
art dealer 
roy lichtensteins kiss ii from 1962 a cartoon image of a 
young couple kissing sold at christies auction house in new york 
city on monday for 6 million the highest price ever paid for a 
work by the artist its presale estimate was 5 million to 7 
million 
at that same sale 26 artworks out of 77 offered failed to find 
buyers because no bids reached the minimum set by the seller the 
auction house sold 4017 million worth of art well below its 
presale estimate of 50 million to 718 million 
at rival sothebys on tuesday 32 artworks out of 87 went 
unsold and the sale brought in 559 million against house 
expectations of 866 million to 1129 million 
still cy twomblys 1971 untitled blackboard painting fetched 
55 million the most ever paid at auction for a work by the 
artist 
i think a lot of the hysteria has gone out of the market 
said milton esterow editor and publisher of artnews 
allan stone a new york dealer agreed whats been going on 
the last couple years has been absolute insanity he said 
they said selective buying was replacing the buying sprees of 
the last several years but the change doesnt indicate the art 
market had hit rocky times 
i think the business will remain very good said gagosian 
some experts particularly art dealers have blamed sothebys 
and christies for creating unrealistic price expectations among 
consignors who place their art with the auction houses for sale 
the problem i think is that too many collectors are too 
greedy and the auction houses have not put their feet down strongly 
enough in telling collectors that their reserves have no relation 
to reality esterow said 
auction houses and sellers agree to a reserve price below which 
an artwork cannot be sold it is in our interest to give the 
consigner the most accurate estimate we can its also in our 
interest to make sure the painting sells nash said 
david nash senior vice president in charge of fine arts at 
