<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh said 
wednesday he has asked congress to stiffen criminal penalties for 
cross burnings and other forms of racial harassment that do not 
result in personal injuries 
the proposed amendments to the landmark 1968 civil rights act 
would make cross burnings a felony under federal law punishable by 
a fiveyear prison sentence and a fine up to 250000 
the offense is now a misdemeanor that carries a maximum oneyear 
sentence and a 100000 fine 
misdemeanor penalties would be retained to allow prosecutors to 
bring lesser charges in appropriate cases the department said in a 
letter to congress 
the harsher penalties are proposed for what thornburgh called 
particularly egregious cases those where firearms are used or 
fire or threats of fire including cross burnings are employed 
thornburghs statement cited a case in which people who burned 
down a home rented by a black family were prosecuted for a 
misdemeanor because there were no injuries 
the law would also apply to situations in which shots are fired 
into homes but there are no injuries prosecutors would have to 
prove racial or ethnic harassment motivated the incident 
in another case prosecutors could only bring misdemeanor 
charges against people accused of burning down a house trailer 
occupied by a biracial family thornburgh said 
the proposed amendments deal with the use or the threat of force 
to interfere with a citizens right to fair housing 
the message of hatred and violence that cross burnings convey 
inflicts enormous psychological damage on victims particularly 
children who live in a targeted house the justice department 
said its letter to congress last month that was released wednesday 
frequently lives are disrupted as families flee neighborhoods 
altogether or members alter schedules to protect their families and 
homes said the letter by bruce c navarro the acting head of 
the departments legislative affairs office 
state charges of arson may be filed by local prosecutors in many 
jurisdictions these crimes carry heavier penalties 
but cross burning is often treated as malicious mischief and 
shootings that do not result in injuries may be minor felonies 
such as assault or attempted assault 
local authorities may not be willing to invest the time to 
investigate a crime that carries a light penalty said daniel 
rinzel head of the justice department unit that prosecutes hate 
crimes 
most cross burnings take some work to try to figure out who 
did it rinzel said 
there are some incidents that you could consider to be serious 
simply because people were lucky they werent injured but are 
nonetheless treated as misdemeanors by the law rinzel said 
 
</TEXT>
