<TEXT>
failure by the us military to issue a 
warning before attacking panamanian defense force headquarters may 
have led to the deaths of dozens of civilians living nearby a 
report said wednesday 
some 15000 persons were left homeless in the attack and a 
very rough estimate is that 50 to 70 civilians were killed 
according to the americas watch study conducted after the december 
invasion of panama 
many more were seriously wounded the report said 
the pentagon had no immediate comment 
americas watch which promotes human rights in latin america and 
the caribbean contends that both the us and panamanian military 
violated international humanitarian law governing armed conflict 
it said the us military failed to observe the laws of war in 
its attack on the pdf headquarters located in the midst of a poor 
panama city neighborhood called el chorrillo 
the report gave little credence to allegations by some observers 
that forces loyal to gen manuel antonio noriega were responsible 
for fires that broke out in el chorrillo and left numerous civilian 
casualties 
noriega was ousted by the invading force and later brought to 
the united states for trial on drug trafficking charges 
the study said us military leaders were unable to cite 
military necessity such as the need for surprise as a reason for 
not informing el chorrillo residents that an attack was imminent 
roman catholic priests said in january that about 20 people died 
in el chorrillo many in a fire set by retreating paramilitary 
supporters of noriega they said that nearly 10000 people sought 
refuge in the church and the school and a home for the elderly next 
to it 
the rev javier arteta said members of the panamanian 
paramilitary dignity battalions bear much of the blame for the 
casualties 
they came out of their homes shooting in every direction 
arteta said adding that the us military never fired in the 
direction of the church 
the americas watch report also said the us military failed to 
follow the laws of war in refusing to free prisoners after 
hostilities ceased 
noriegas forces violated international law by taking civilian 
hostages and by dressing as civilians during the fighting thus 
attracting fire and exposing innocent people to combat the report 
said 
the study said the us southern command in panama undercounted 
the number of civilian deaths the pentagon total was 202 but the 
report said 300 was more likely the real figure 
former us attorney general ramsey clark has estimated the 
death toll at 4000 to 7000 but the report said there was no 
basis for such a finding 
