republicans losing several votes on 
amendments abandoned efforts wednesday night to stall senate 
action on a bill loosening restrictions on political activities by 
government workers 
gop leader bob dole of kansas agreed to allow a vote late 
thursday on final passage of the wholesale revisions in the 1939 
hatch act which now forbids federal employees from participating 
actively in partisan politics 
majority leader george mitchell dmaine said the senate would 
then proceed to consideration friday of rival campaign finance 
bills in the hope of finding a bipartisan compromise by the end of 
next week 
mitchell however acknowledged tat a compromise will require 
some backroom negotiations with dole and others 
in the meatime he said democrats will try next week to pass a 
bill authorizing 300 million a year in emergency aid for 13 cities 
whose public health systems face collapse because of local aids 
epidemics 
the 13 cities are atlanta boston chicago dallas houston los 
angeles miami new york newark nj philadelphia san 
francisco washington and san juan puerto rico 
under the agreement on the bill to revise the hatch act 
republicans may offer nine more amendments including one by dole 
to continue the current restrictions on employees in intelligence 
agencies the justice department the internal revenue service and 
the federal election commission 
a similar amendment by dole was defeated 5146 tuesday 
earlier wednesday democrats overwhelmingly beat back a 
republican effort to make federal employee unions refund part of 
the dues paid by members who disgree with the organizations 
political stands or endorsements 
on a 6335 vote the senate rejected an amendment by sen mitch 
mcconnell rky to force the dues rebates as part of a bill 
loosening restrictions on political activities by 3 million 
government civil service and postal workers 
mcconnell said his amendment would remove for federal workers 
the hobsons choice of having to pick between getting out of a 
union and losing their voice in collective bargaining or accepting 
the use of a portion of their dues for political causes they dont 
support 
a similar measure is one of the main features of the gops 
version of a campaign finance reform bill introduced wednesday in 
the senate 
both seek to write into law and expand a 1988 supreme court 
decision that workers who pay fees to labor organizations under 
union shop agreements can demand a rebate of any portion of those 
fees not devoted to collective bargaining 
the bill already approved in a broader form by the house would 
lift most of the current offthejob restrictions on political 
activities by government workers under the 51yearold hatch act 
also defeated on a 6236 vote was an amendment by dole to let 
workers in each federal agency decide by majority vote whether to 
accept a loosening of the rules on their outside political 
activites 
the senate spent more than a week on the legislation with 
majority democrats joined by about a dozen republicans rejecting a 
series of amendments by the gop leadership to maintain the 
restrictions 
president bushs senior advisers have said they would urge him 
to veto any change in the law as undermining the integrity and 
independence of the traditionally nonpartisan civil service 
