<TEXT>
one legacy of the exxon valdez disaster 
has been several spill bills to strengthen alaskas pollution 
laws but two tough antispill measures have run aground on 
legislative shoals 
gov steve cowper said wednesday he was pleased with the bills 
that passed before tuesday nights adjournment deadline but he 
said the oil industry had played a major role in preventing 
stronger bills from passing 
they weakened the legislation that passed and they probably 
were instrumental in stopping the bills that didnt get through 
cowper said 
the democraticcontrolled house sent six oilspill bills to the 
republicanled senate which killed a major enforcement bill house 
republicans meanwhile stopped the only senatepassed bill in 
their chamber 
in addition some provisions on bills that passed were weakened 
by the legislature cowper said 
nonetheless he said state industry and federal government 
measures since the spill will help prevent another disaster like 
the exxon valdez the worst oil spill in the nations history 
the tanker struck a charted reef on march 24 1989 and spilled 
nearly 11 million gallons of north slope crude in the hitherto 
pristine waters of prince william sound 
walt parker chairman of the alaska oil spill commission which 
investigated the exxon valdez disaster said the oil industrys 
massive lobbying presence against the bills was understandable 
it is their no 1 priority to have no state involvement in the 
oil transportation system parker said 
a house bill that would set strict standards for oilindustry 
cleanup plans including a 72hour requirement for response to 
major spills had to wait until the final hours of the session 
before winning senate approval 
its not a performance standard its a planning standard 
said dennis kelso commissioner of the state department of 
environmental conservation 
the measure also requires companies either to prove they can pay 
spill cleanup costs or risk a state shutdown of their operations 
although revamped in senate committee the bill is still worth 
having kelso said 
a tough enforcement and inspection bill died in the senate 
resources committee when the session adjourned 
the original bill would have let the department of environmental 
conservation order companies to pay for independent audits of 
pollution problems the senate version said companies could refuse 
the states request 
the senate judiciary panel removed a provision allowing 
warrantless searches of suspected polluters replacing it with a 
plan allowing such searches only if agreed on as part of the 
companys operating permit 
the bill also was changed to give companies more time to obey 
state compliance orders for correcting violations of environmental 
laws 
house republicans blocked passage of a senate bill that would 
have increased municipal access to the states oilspill fund 
which is financed by a 5centabarrel tax on alaska oil production 
the new tax was instituted last year as an immediate response to 
the tanker accident and the bill would have increased municipal 
access to the fund for cleanup and other emergency costs 
other bills that won legislative approval and were sent to the 
governor include measures that would 
increase criminal penalties for negligent operation of oil 
tankers 
establish a citizens oversight council on oil and other 
hazardous substances 
establish state management plans for oilspill response 
efforts 
increase corporate fines for negligence in oil spills and 
other crimes 
