<TEXT>
a judge who once granted chippewa indians 
100 percent of the fish caught in northern wisconsin ruled 
wednesday that the regions harvestable natural resources 
should be divided 5050 between indians and nonindians 
us district judge barbara crabbs decision which came in a 
case that set parameters for deer hunting has sweeping 
implications that limit the tribes right to half the available 
fish and timber in northern wisconsin lawyers said 
under treaties that ceded the northern third of the state to the 
united states in the 19th century wisconsins six chippewa bands 
retain the right to spearfish hunt and cut timber offreservation 
on public lands in the region 
since a court affirmed the treaties in 1983 the chippewa have 
exercised their spearfishing rights on northern lakes encountering 
huge and sometimes violent protests by opponents who claim the 
special treaty rights are unfair and threaten to deplete fish and 
timber resources 
wednesdays decision contrasts with mrs crabbs previous ruling 
that the chippewa are entitled to 100 percent of the safe 
allowable catch of fish in the 23929 square miles of territory 
ceded in the 19th century 
state lawyers said the new ruling essentially alters the 
previous decision 
its our understanding of this decision that it does not apply 
only to deer but that it applies to all natural resources 
attorney general donald hanaway said and i think thats 
extremely significant 
mrs crabbs office said the judge would not further interpret 
her intentions beyond what was stated in her 74page decision 
since the 1983 court ruling the chippewa bands have filed a 
series of lawsuits asking the court to define how much of the 
resources of northern wisconsin they are entitled to under the 
treaties and to what degree the state can regulate tribal 
activities 
tribal attorneys declined immediate comment on the ruling but 
tom maulson a lac du flambeau chippewa spearfishing coordinator 
and a leader in the treaty rights group waswagon treaty 
association said the philosophy of sharing the resource has been 
supported by the tribe for years 
maulson said the split in allocation of resources did not 
unfairly deprive the chippewa of their rights 
i bet the tribe will never touch 50 percent he said we 
say the resource is for everybody maybe theyll start to realize 
that what weve wanted all along 
administration secretary james klauser the top aide to gov 
tommy g thompson said wednesdays ruling was significant because 
it recognizes the nonindian right to the resources 
the important findings are that the treaty provisions only 
apply to public lands and the state has regulatory authority for 
the hunting seasons he added 
the leader of an antitreaty group said the latest ruling 
wouldnt anger nonindians and could lead to a solution to tensions 
over tribal rights 
i think shes beginning to open the door to cooperation to 
open the door for settlement between all parties said larry 
peterson of the protect americans rights and resources 
the judge said she was setting the deer limit for the chippewa 
at 50 percent of the estimated population based on the tribes 
needs for a moderate standard of living and to prevent the 
frustration of the nonindian treaty right 
</TEXT>
