the socialist government narrowly defeated a 
noconfidence motion introduced after a politician was granted 
amnesty under a widely unpopular law that had been sponsored by the 
governing party 
only 262 deputies voted for the motion 27 short of the majority 
needed in the 577seat national assembly 
if the motion had succeeded premier michel rocards government 
would have been forced to resign leaving president francois 
mitterrand to name a new prime minister or call legislative 
elections 
it was the fifth failed noconfidence motion since mitterrand 
was reelected in 1988 
the assembly passed the socialistproposed amnesty bill in 
december with all communist deputies and many rightists voting 
against it 
the amnesty came as politicians and newspapers began reporting 
that kickbacks on public contracts had become a major source of 
funding for nearly all the established parties 
the opposition says it understood the amnesty law would protect 
contributors but exclude members of the assembly 
they claim the government misrepresented the bill and were 
especially angered when former cooperation minister christian nucci 
received amnesty in the financial scandal 
the amnesty has contributed to mitterrands decline in public 
opinion polls only 39 percent of french citizens expressing 
approval with his performance in a recent newspaper survey 
