<TEXT>
the rainbloated arkansas river reached 
its highest level in 37 years wednesday in flooding that put more 
than 500 homes under water and has drowned or trapped hundreds of 
cattle officials said 
the river began slowly receding after cresting wednesday morning 
at 475 feet at pine bluff about 40 miles southeast of little rock 
the highest its been since reaching 521 feet in 1943 the 
national weather service said 
floods that swamped texas and oklahoma as well as arkansas began 
late last week following heavy rains rains and flooding have 
claimed 12 lives in texas and one in oklahoma but none in 
arkansas officials said 
in texas where 4000 homes have been damaged or destroyed by 
flooding up to 400 volunteers national guard soldiers and 
officials patrolled levees near the arkansas line that threatened 
to give way on the swollen red river 
residents of flooded sections of dallas tried to save what they 
could from homes under several feet of water others began cleaning 
up 
several hundred homes were flooded in oklahoma but the waters 
are starting to go down said civil defense spokesman richard 
hill theres still a lot of places we cant physically reach 
in arkansas about 300 homes in jefferson county which includes 
pine bluff were flooded wednesday and more than 200 homes were 
underwater along the river from that county to fort smith on the 
oklahoma line authorities said about 16000 sandbags were sent to 
jefferson county 
officials say its difficult to estimate the number of people 
evacuated because most are staying with friends or relatives 
rather than at emergency shelters 
about 400 cattle were missing from herds along the river basin 
and were believed to have drowned said arkansas cattlemens 
association president walt rowden 
officials continue to watch the weather said army corps of 
engineers spokesman ron helton 
our biggest concern now is rain helton said our 
lakes are full and they cant handle any more water so it will 
have to come down river 
the white house may declare arkansas a federal disaster area 
later this week state and federal officials said at a news 
conference at little rocks riverfront park as the river rolled by 
at 440000 cubic feet per second 
people could begin receiving federal assistance as early as 
monday if the declaration is signed before the weekend said joe 
brady operations supervisor for the state office of emergency 
services 
no firm estimates on damage were available officials said 
brady estimated damage to roads and bridges at about 10 million 
but said that figure is expected to escalate 
theres no way to get precise counts until the water 
recedes he said 
the floods have caused millions of dollars worth of damage to 
farmers in jefferson county alone the flooding is expected to 
cause an estimated 20 million in damages including reduced rice 
and cotton crops said frank plafcan of the county extension office 
direct losses to cattle ranchers across the river basin are 
expected to top 250000 and expected higher feed costs due to hay 
and alfalfa crops now underwater will add to ranchers woes rowden 
said 
bradley harris regional director for the federal emergency 
management agency said he expects state emergency officials 
assisted by fema personnel to complete preliminary damage surveys 
by thursday or friday that information will be forwarded to the 
white house 
in another development corps officials continued to discount 
complaints the flooding was worse because of mismanagement along 
the mcclellankerr arkansas river navigation system 
buddy dyke of swan lake where about 35 families have been 
forced to leave their homes complained about misinformation from 
the corps 
they said it was going to crest on monday then tuesday then 
wednesday then in pine bluff on thursday said buddy dyke of 
swan lake where about 35 families have been forced to leave their 
homes itll probably be here on friday 
he said the river rose several feet higher than residents were 
told to expect cut off from land they didnt have time to move 
out valuables 
col charles mccloskey with the little rock district of the army 
engineers said in little rock that water would have been higher in 
most places without the navigation system and said the system 
worked like it was supposed to 
pj spaul another corps spokesman said earlier this week that 
flood damage would have been three to four times greater without 
the levee system the reservoir system in oklahoma prevented 
another 105 million in damages in arkansas he said 
among those with trapped cattle was state rep lloyd george of 
danville who has about 150 head stranded on 40 dry acres on a 
2000acre pasture 
obviously thats not enough for them to feed on said 
george whos paying 100 a day to feed cattle that otherwise would 
graze 
im concerned about these cattle he said if i have to 
keep feeding them it gets expensive 
