<TEXT>
a jury wednesday found a man guilty of 
trying to poison the historic treaty oak a centuriesold tree that 
was severely damaged by the powerful herbicide velpar 
paul stedman cullen 46 faces a possible life sentence because 
of a prior conviction he has been jailed since his arrest in june 
1989 state district judge bob perkins scheduled the sentencing 
phase of the trial for thursday 
cullen stood expressionless as the verdict was read after about 
three and onehalf hours of deliberation he refused to comment as 
he was led from the courtroom 
prosecutors contended that cullen used the powerful herbicide 
velpar to poison the centuriesold live oak tree in a ritual 
apparently designed to end his affection for his counselor at a 
methadone clinic 
legend has it that the giant live oak estimated to be at least 
500 years old was the site of a treaty signing between stephen f 
austin and indians during the 1820s 
prosecutors during the 1week trial produced a tape recording 
in which cullen told cindy blaco he had killed the tree adding 
the only evidence is my mouth 
cullens defense lawyers said cullen was lying to try to impress 
ms blaco who secretly taped the conversation for police 
they contended that ms blaco may have been testifying to 
collect more than 11000 in rewards the defense also called 
witnesses who said cullen wasnt interested in the occult but was 
prone to telling outrageous lies 
ms blaco testified that during february 1989 when experts 
believe the tree was poisoned cullen had several books on 
witchcraft and the occult she also testified that she saw two 
containers of velpar in the back of cullens truck that month 
since the poisoning was discovered last memorial day more than 
100000 has been donated as city foresters and outside experts 
have taken extraordinary measures to save the tree 
velparcontaminated earth was removed from around its roots the 
tree has been doused with spring water and shaded by elaborate sun 
screens but foresters say at least half the oak is dead 
