pope john paul ii speaking to an 
audience of mexicos wealthiest businessmen assailed the idea that 
capitalism has beaten socialism and said wednesday that mexico is 
still very far from the ideal of justice 
he said the poor had suffered the worst consequences of mexicos 
economic crisis and accused the small powerful upperclass of 
generating even more poverty 
the events of recent history have been interpreted 
sometimes in a superficial way as the triumph of the liberal 
capitalist system john paul said in a speech in durango a 
provincial capital 450 miles northwest of mexico city 
some interests would like to take the analysis to the extreme 
of presenting the system they consider the winner as the only way 
for our world but he said that conclusion avoids the necessary 
critical judgment about the effects that liberal capitalism has 
produced in the socalled third world countries 
on the fourth day of his trip here the pope earlier wednesday 
visited a state prison and spent 20 minutes greeting and blessing 
inmates including murderers and drug traffickers 
wednesday evening the pope ordained 100 new priests during a 
