<TEXT>
the task of managing money in a personal 
retirement plan brings out the cautious streak in many american 
savers 
with their longterm future resting heavily on individual 
retirement accounts employersponsored 401k plans and similar 
taxfavored arrangements they tend to see these nest eggs as too 
important to be exposed to the risks of volatile markets 
hence theres a widespread appetite for interestbearing 
investments especially those covered by some sort of guarantee 
rather than alternatives that are subject to the ups and downs of 
the securities markets 
for example even after the runaway bull market in stocks of the 
1980s more than half of all americans individual retirement 
account assets was on deposit at banks savings institutions and 
credit unions 
about 22 percent of the total ira assets of 393 billion as of 
the end of 1988 was entrusted to mutual funds according to 
estimates by the investment company institute a trade group 
whats more within the mutual funds share of the ira business 
54 percent of the money was invested in income and money market 
funds leaving 46 percent entrusted to managers of stock funds 
most experts on the subject agree that these statistics show a 
justified sense of prudence 
retirement accounts are designed to foster longterm saving not 
speculative financing of highrisk ventures some of the tax rules 
covering them reinforce that basic principle 
ordinarily a capital loss on something such as a stockmarket 
investment can be written off against your ordinary income up to a 
limit of 3000 per year on your tax return no such consolation 
is available however within retirement accounts that provide for 
deferral of any income taxation until withdrawals begin 
yet with all this many financial advisers say it is easy to get 
too cautious in your retirement saving choices overemphasizing 
safety of your dollar investment while overlooking the hazards of 
inflation 
the longer the time you have before retirement they say the 
stronger the historical case for stock marketrelated investments 
over a long time horizon an equity portfolio should perform 
at least as well as and most likely better than a fixedincome 
portfolio says the accounting firm of deloitte amp touche in a 
current bulletin on the subject 
for all 20year periods starting in any month dating back to 
1926 the standard amp poors 500stock composite index posted a 
better return than was available from treasury bills the firm says 
stock returns vary drastically they reached 193 percent a year 
in the 1950s fell to 59 percent by the 1970s and rebounded to 
175 percent in the 1980s according to the investment management 
firm of t rowe price associates 
however says deloitte amp touche people who make regular 
contributions to retirement savings programs actually can turn 
these ups and downs to their benefit through the phenomenon known 
as dollar cost averaging 
when similar dollar amounts are invested at intervals in say a 
stock mutual fund the money buys more shares at lower prices 
helping to reduce the average price paid per share 
the periodic investing that occurs in retirement accounts 
which is in effect dollar cost averaging has a much more 
positive effect on volatile investments than on nonvolatile 
investments deloitte amp touche notes 
the risk in this of course is that stocks in the future might 
not live up to the standards of the past in an investment that 
drops steadily over time and never rebounds dollarcost averaging 
isnt much help 
but over the past couple of generations longterm investors 
have been amply rewarded for taking that chance 
</TEXT>
