plans to continue ryans work in aids education from their home 
about 20 miles north of indianapolis 
already she has testified on capitol hill for the passage of a 
bill that would provide 600 million to help fight aids the senate 
labor and human resources committee approved the legislation last 
month and dedicated the bill to ryan 
a member of the american federation for aids research mrs 
white traveled to new york city to speak about aids on world kids 
day may 6 
the torch has been passed 
im just going to try and work in the back of things if 
progress can be made through ryans name im going to work through 
it i want to work any way i can she said 
ryan contracted aids from a blood byproduct used to treat his 
hemophilia his mother knew he would have health problems when he 
was only a few days old was circumcised and bled profusely at 5 
he began twiceweekly injections to help clot his blood 
mrs white said she thought the blood byproduct was a miracle 
drug because at that time hemophiliacs lived only to age 12 or 13 
little did we know that the same thing we thought would save 
them would destroy them she said nobody told us where they 
get the blood they pay people to donate it chances are that ryan 
got it from an iv drug user but it could have been from anybody 
thats why we never pointed any fingers 
the whites were unable to sue the company that produced the 
blood product because of a state law that bars lawsuits for 
illnesses stemming from blood or blood derivatives 
mrs white said she wont fight the law im through with 
attorneys she said 
the family did however win a legal battle to keep ryan in 
public school he was barred from western middle school nea kokomo 
in 1985 because school officials feared the health risk for other 
children was too great 
the courts finally ruled that ryan could attend school his 
courage and determination captured the hearts of people worldwide 
and suddenly he was in demand as a spokesman 
