records riopelle cant afford a cd player and said he prefers the 
look of an album with its cover art and liner notes to a cassette 
its disconcerting he said when he can find his favorite 
alternative rock albums only in the import bin priced higher than 
cds i would like to be able to continue to buy them and not have 
the latest technology shoved down my throat 
merchants still interested in stocking records say return 
policies and reordering difficulties are putting pressure on them 
to relent 
many record companies charge a penalty for return of an unsold 
record for instance konrad said hell get only 450 to return a 
record for which he paid 6 even if its defective but theres no 
penalty for cassette and cd returns 
the decisions of so many record companies not to accept returns 
on 7inch singles is what drove tower records out of the business 
of 45s store managers had to worry about ordering too few records 
and selling out or ordering too many and being left with worthless 
extras 
konrad said hes continually frustrated in ordering new copies 
of records hes ordered copies of keith richards talk is 
cheap album every week since september and in late march still 
hadnt gotten any hes had only one shipment of the b52s cosmic 
thing album on vinyl and its a top 10 hit 
rocky roy owner of the music shack in albany tries to keep new 
records in stock because many of his musichungry customers arent 
willing to risk 15 for a cd of an artist they barely know 
a recent experience by chrysalis shows the volatility of this 
changeover the second album by irish singer sinead oconnor 
released in late march was initially one of the albums the record 
company planned to release only on cd and cassette 
oconnor coming from a country where vinyl still reigns cried 
foul chrysalis relented and printed records and stotter said 
the company received almost 40000 orders for lps before the album 
was even released far more than it expected 
stotter admitted he underestimated the appeal of vinyl for 
oconnors new album which has topped the charts since its release 
but it doesnt change his opinion that the days of vinyl are 
numbered and he says the industry is innocent of forcing the trend 
i dont think the record companies are trying to kill it off 
at all he said its the people who frequent records stores 
who are showing less and less interest in records 
as a collector with thousands of records herself heimer 
sympathizes with record fanatics but the one or two or 12 or 100 
lp buyers who are shouting that theyre killing it off prematurely 
just arent buying millions of lps to make it worthwhile for the 
companies she said 
the fast disappearance of lps has given rise to a new type of 
