<TEXT>
the supreme court this weeks takes up 
congress attempt to protect the american flag from desecration 
while the issue before the justices is the laws constitutionality 
politics wont be far below the surface 
the high court will hear arguments monday and is expected to 
rule by the time its current term ends probably in late june or 
early july if the law is struck down a proposed constitutional 
amendment to protect the flag almost certainly would become a 
leading issue in congressional and state legislative races this 
fall 
the onehour argument session is extraordinary on only three 
occasions in recent times has the court heard arguments on a case 
so late in a session 
the law the flag protection act of 1989 makes it a crime 
punishable by up to a year in prison for anyone who burns 
mutilates defaces or tramples on the flag or maintains it on 
the floor or ground 
the court will examine its past rulings on the first amendment 
safeguards of free speech and expression 
while the bush administration defends the law its no secret 
president bush and leading republicans would prefer a 
constitutional amendment to ban flag burning something that would 
be unnecessary if the justices uphold the law 
the prime sponsors of the law are democrats who learned a 
bitter lesson from the 1988 presidential campaign in which bush 
exploited patriotic values in defeating gov michael dukakis of 
massachusetts 
new york gov mario cuomo possibly a future democratic 
presidential contender put the matter in perspective in a brief 
submitted to the high court 
if the law is struck down the brief said there will be a 
serious and profound impact on new york and other states because 
such a ruling would almost certainly trigger a divisive battle in 
congress and in the states over whether a constitutional amendment 
to permit a ban on flag burning should be passed 
the speaker of the house rep thomas s foley dwash has 
promised a house vote on a constitutional amendment within 30 days 
if the court invalidates the law 
such an amendment proclaiming that a ban on flag burning does 
not violate free speech would require approval by twothirds of 
the members of the house and senate and then ratification by 38 
state legislatures 
the first amendment has not been modified since it took force 
199 years ago 
when lawyers for the administration and demonstrators who have 
burned flags address the court monday they may target justice 
harry a blackmun more than the other eight jurists 
blackmun voted with the majority in june when the justices by a 
54 margin struck down a texas law barring desecration or 
destruction of the flag the court said that burning the flag as a 
form of political protest is protected by the constitutions 
freespeech guarantees 
but blackmun in a 1974 ruling indicated he might go along with 
some laws to protect the flags physical integrity 
in that case blackmun dissented as the court threw out the 
conviction of a massachusetts man who wore a small flag on the seat 
of his pants 
the flag protection act was a reaction to the courts june 
ruling and the political firestorm that followed 
house democratic leaders say the law differs from the texas 
statute because the federal act does not single out flag burning as 
a means of expression 
the texas law specifically banned flag burning that seriously 
offends others 
the federal law forbids defiling or destruction of the flag for 
any purpose except to destroy a soiled or tattered flag 
the justice department in a written brief to the court said 
it is the physical assault and accompanying violation of the 
flags physical integrity not robust and uninhibited debate 
that occasion the injury that our society should not be called upon 
to bear 
moreover the department said the court owes congress special 
deference in this case because an equal branch of government has 
determined flag burning can be outlawed without violating freedom 
of speech 
lawyers for the demonstrators said their clients consider flag 
burning an essential element of their political expression because 
for them the flag represents not glory but oppression 
they also said flag desecration has been an american tradition 
the united states flag was born of a desecration the lawyers 
said george washington in 1776 defaced a british flag by 
ordering sewn upon it 13 red and white stripes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900509-0212 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
four years ago a band called poi dog pondering 
gathered once a week under swaying palm trees in front of a 
woolworths store in waikiki playing for small change from bemused 
tourists 
today the group has a sevenalbum contract with columbia 
records after an agonizing eightmonth major label bidding war 
that was won primarily when columbias president intervened to woo 
the band 
besides the record deal poi dog has acquired other 
accoutrements of success a manager a lawyer videos on music 
television and a european tour their debut album with columbia 
wishing like a mountain thinking like the sea was released 
last month 
the journey from lava rock to black rock cbss monolithic black 
marble headquarters in manhattan began in 1986 when poi dogs 
leader frank orrall proposed that anyone who wanted to tour the 
mainland show up at honolulu international airport 
nine took the leap and ended up cramming all their instruments 
and belongings into two cars for an extended openended 
crosscountry trip not knowing where they would go or how they 
would support themselves two of the original group remain in the 
band today 
poi dog hawaiian slang for a mixbreed dog is a fitting 
moniker for the group that combines the usual guitar bass and 
drums with the notsousual latvian lap harp an accordian the 
flugelhorn tin whistle wood block and somebodys used frying pan 
for five months the musical caravan rambled across the 
continent on the road and off orrall wrote songs that combined 
earthy imagery with a focus on love and death endured lifes pain 
and reveled in its joy most songs have upbeat flourishes that have 
led some critics to grumble that the tunes are just too happy 
during their meanderings orrall nurtured a contract deal with 
texas hotel records based in santa monica calif he met the 
labels owners michael meister and susan farrell in 1984 when 
they had a record store texas records that catered to alternative 
bands and small labels bands such as rem 10000 maniacs and 
concrete blonde stopped by the store to play for free 
meister and farrell later closed the shop to join forces with 
steve tesluk to create a label full of ripe acts including former 
black flag leader henry rollins and his band downy mildew and new 
acts such as baby flamehead and new chestnut 
orrall liked the people at texas hotel because they were such 
defenders of the young and the raw poi dog made two ep records 
with texas hotel under a fivealbum contract but the terms were 
not ironclad 
poi dog began to get gigs and huge exposure at major 
recording industry conventions and the suits as those from 
independent labels like to derisively call major label record 
executives were hungry for the alternative sound one that 
doesnt generally rely on synthesizers or heavy technology in the 
recording studio 
alternative songs also shy away from traditional pop and rock 
structures and often combine influences from other cultures and 
ethnic groups recording is cheaper done in fewer takes and rarely 
is heavily remixed sometimes giving it more of a garage band feel 
and alternative music is rooted in idealism music for musics 
sake and not for commerical prosperity 
poi dogs big break came in 1988 when texas hotel arranged 
several gigs at the new music seminar in new york city a hotbed of 
record execs looking for the next new big thing 
the group traveled by van once again to new york a trip that 
was chronicled by avantgarde filmmaker and animator laura 
margulies who is currently working on an animation for a future 
music video 
thats when people became interested orrall said record 
executives called aamprs for artist and repertoire started 
appearing at poi dog concerts 
one was michael hill who was scouting sounds for warner bros 
i thought they were fun hill said but i didnt get a great 
impression of them one way or another 
a few months later hill saw them in a better venue and became 
an instant fan i was just knocked out by it 
hill made overtures and told orrall hed like to talk more he 
also began to follow the group around the country like a school 
boy with a bad case of puppy love 
by the time they reached austin for the southbysouthwest 
music conference it was so out of control everyone in the 
business came to the show they were great hill said 
one aampr executive who took notice was columbias michael 
gallelli i heard their music on tape before i saw them he 
said and it was really one of those things where i was a fan 
first 
he liked poi dogs diverse influences they were combining 
lots of different styles like african to caribbean to celtic 
infuences i thought that was really great that they were able to 
bring it all together and then there was a storytelling aspect 
that i really liked 
in the meantime thoughts of playing an east coast gig were 
making orrall nervous because he knew that after the last song was 
performed the stage would be overtaken by a tribe of record execs 
by that time even though orrall wasnt rushing to sign with 
anyone it was boiling down to a deal with either warner bros or 
aampm 
warners with its solid reputation as a haven for independent 
alternative music interested orrall but the label wasnt sure if 
it could sign poi dog he said because they had a lot going on 
with other bands aampm which had been independently owned and was 
in the process of being bought out was tempting but the prospect 
of new ownership made the band nervous 
we were on texas hotel we had all the creative freedom that 
we wanted we could do anything he said it was a perfect 
situation i was in no hurry to give any of that away for a bigger 
venue 
enter don ienner columbia records president and chief suitor 
