<TEXT>
whats on the dinner table in the 1990s may 
represent one of the most tangible legacies of the 1960s even for 
those who never sprouted a bean 
the rebellion by health food nuts against plastic food 
was part of a bigger effort to live better that included the civil 
rights environmental and womens movements warren j belasco 
argues in appetite for change how the counterculture took on the 
food industry 19661988 published by pantheon books 
in his preface including the story of his discovery of 
alternative ways of eating belasco connects the dinner table to 
the political changes of the 1960s 
indeed ive found that rather than just being silly or 
perverse as our parents and skeptical peers probably thought we 
were cooking up something quite serious ambitious and yes 
radical an alternative food system with its own ideology staples 
and supply lines a countercuisine 
food he said often is ignored by analysts of our history and 
culture belasco in fact began his research intending to write 
about how the mainstream coopted counterculture efforts in rock 
n roll clothing and food the food just became too big 
the new left argued over and over that the personal was 
political and belasco argues nothing is more personal than food 
and what could be more political than challenging agribusiness 
americas largest and most evironmentally troublesome industry 
i really do think that food is one of the most substantial 
parts of our lives central to our health and our pleasure he 
said in a telephone interview from the university of maryland 
where he is an american studies professor 
belasco presents an engaging and copiously footnoted tale 
that connects food giveaways in the haightashbury of the mid1960s 
to the chocolatecovered granola bars that pass for healthy kids 
food today 
he adds spice to his theories by liberally quoting many 
underground food columnists of the 1960s appetite for change 
is not just fun though it is that it forces readers to consider 
whats in their pantries and why 
business figured out pretty quickly that the countercuisine 
could be profitable and today the profusion of socalled health 
and lite foods is ironic evidence of success of course the 
legacy also exists in food cooperatives concern over health 
organic farms and other alternative enterprises 
but the countercuisine has not turned us into a nation of 
healthy socially conscious eaters and belasco tries to explain 
why the supermarket is an additive minefield processors are 
consolidating rapidly the farm belt is a disaster area pesticides 
are out of control and we reek with contradictions like everyone 
else 
the reasons are complicated the fault of the ecofreaks as 
well as the food industry there were plenty of conflicts 
vegetarians vs meateaters white bread vs wholegrain brown 
convenience vs homemade natural vs processed ethnic dishes vs 
wasp food 
belasco also criticizes the press and the response in the 70s 
to public concerns about the food supply by a government that was 
itself a bundle of contraditions inconsistencies and 
vacillations 
and there were disputes within the counterculture over the role 
of food communes and cooperatives and hip capitalists 
it may now be hard to see revoluntionary significance in the 
eating of unhulled rice and curried carrots or granola and yogurt 
in 196970 however dietary change was one of the more substantial 
household reforms belasco writes 
twenty years later americans are again being coaxed to make 
changes that start at home consume green recycle conserve 
its good that there is all this news but im kind of 
skeptical as to how deep it is as far as earth day belasco said 
in the interview i had very mixed feelings about that as a 
really meaningful set of activities on that day 
green sounds today a lot like natural did 20 years ago 
hard to define and therefore open to fraud and real change is 
slow he noted 
the problem is the public is not going to see immediate 
gains he said people like me im a believer and im in 
there for the long pull 
todays news seems all too familiar a lot of this is deja vu 
to me we went through this 20 years ago and i think a lot of it 
got coopted he said beyond defining the content of food 
natural was a liberated state of mind a symbol of opposition to 
mass production efficiency rationalization limits 
at the other end of the spectrum massproduced processed 
food encouraged alientation from nature society ones own body 
unfortunately most consumers seemed to collaborate in their own 
alientation 
but he said he is a bit more optimistic today than even two 
years ago when he finished his book with the lessthan enthusiastic 
plea that since the odds against us were always steep i suppose 
theres no reason to lose heart now 
