<DOCNO> AP900509-0229 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after months of hinting at its position the 
bush administration is siding with the securities and exchange 
commission in its jurisdictional dispute with futures regulators 
treasury undersecretary robert glauber told a senate panel 
tuesday that the administration will introduce legislation to strip 
the commodity futures trading commission of control over 
stockindex futures and hand it to the sec 
the announcement marks a victory for the sec which regulates 
the nations stock markets in a turf battle with the rival cftc 
which oversees futures markets 
the dispute centers on which agency should oversee financial 
products that have elements of both a security and a futures 
contract these socalled hybrid products include stockindex 
futures 
in testimony before the senate agriculture committee which 
oversees the cftc glauber said the administration wants the sec to 
have authority over all stockrelated products including 
stockindex futures and stockindex options 
sen patrick leahy the committee chairman said he would ask 
the leadership to bring the matter to the senate floor for action 
he did so after berating both the sec and cftc for their 
increasingly combative rhetoric and complaining that the measure 
might delay muchneeded futures market reform 
reaction from the futures exchanges was swift and predictable 
in chicago thomas r donovan chairman of the chicago board of 
trade said the proposal would solve a perceived problem only to 
create a very real one by placing futures markets under two 
regulators 
the proposal is clearly just the first step of creeping 
regulatory imperialism he added in a lengthy statement released 
by the cbot 
such a move could serve to endanger our nations number one 
status in the world in financial services said leo melamed 
chairman of the chicago mercantile exchanges executive committee 
that is a risk that congress ought not take he said in a 
statement 
john damgard president of the futures industry association who 
sat in on the hearing said therell be no jurisdictional change 
this year but it sure mucks up the reauthorization scene which i 
think everybody will agree is unfortunate 
in his opening remarks leahy complained the dispute has held up 
passage of a bill that adds several market reform measures to the 
cftcs reauthorization legislation 
congress remains blocked from enacting the tough reforms we 
all agreed are needed the vermont democrat said 
leahy also said the committee should consider responsible 
appropriate solutions possibly even the ultimate merger of the 
sec and cftc if this is shown to be justified and feasible 
cftc chairman wendy gramm told the committee a change in 
jurisdiction could cripple her agency 
splitting off stock index or financial futures from the cftc 
would result in the loss of some of our most experienced personnel 
which could damage agency morale and threaten our ability to 
oversee the remaining markets within our jursidiction she said 
in addition to glauber and gramm federal reserve board chairman 
alan greenspan and sec chairman richard breeden also testified 
before the committee the four witnesses sit on the white house 
working group on financial markets which was set up in the wake of 
the 1987 stock market crash to handle intermarket issues 
</TEXT>
