<TEXT>
americas blackowned businesses slumped notably 
last year and must get leaner stronger better to cope with 
big debt burdens and a less favorable stance by the government 
black enterprise magazine reported 
hit by the sluggish economy the nations biggest blackowned 
businesses saw employment fall sharply and sales decline last year 
the magazine said tuesday 
in its annual tally of the biggest blackowned us businesses 
the magazine said the coming years posed even more hurdles because 
of cutbacks in areas such as defense spending and what it deemed 
weakening government commitments to affirmative action and minority 
aid programs 
black entrepreneurs will have to rethink their strategic focus 
and restructure their organizations if they are to keep their 
competitive edge and reap profits from the ensuing chaos said 
earl g graves editor and publisher in other words black 
business is going to have to get leaner stronger better 
among the 100 biggest industrial and service companies 
employment fell by 104 percent while sales dropped 38 percent to 
446 billion the magazine stated 
for the 100 biggest blackowned auto dealerships which are 
listed separately sales rose by 84 percent to 233 billion but 
total staff dropped 13 percent reflecting the slowdown in the 
nations auto industry 
nineteen of the biggest companies from 1988 twothirds of them 
auto dealerhips sought bankruptcy court protection from creditors 
during the year 
retaining the top spot among industrial and service companies 
was tlc beatrice international holdings co the foods processor 
and distributor the new yorkbased holding company acquired the 
international food businesses of the former beatrice cos in a 
debtfinanced 985 million buyout in 1987 
tlc beatrices gross sales of 151 billion accounted for about 
a third of the total sales of the be 100 biggest industrial and 
service companies 
but like many of the other companies tlc beatrice suffered from 
weak conditions in the economy and financial markets a planned 
public offering of 35 percent of the company which would have made 
tlc beatrice the first blackowned company on the new york stock 
exchange was withdrawn in december due to a sagging stock market 
and a weak reception by investors 
in short be 100s companies like much of american industry 
are paying for the excesses of the 1980s the magazine stated 
debtridden and immurred in cyclical industries many be 100s 
companies realize that the flush times are over or at least 
stalled 
not only will black businesses have to confront an economy 
chugging at a much slower pace but they must profit as national 
state and local government agencies begin to reregulate sagging 
industries and develop an increasingly laissez faire attitude about 
affirmative action and minority setasides the magazine said 
johnson publishing co inc of chicago the publisher 
broadcaster and maker of cosmetics and haircare products retained 
second place on the list with 2413 million in revenue 
j bruce llewellyns philadelphia cocacola bottling co inc 
the soft drink bottler kept third place with 240 million in 
sales 
hj russell amp co of atlanta involved in construction 
property management and food and beverages held fourth place 
although its revenue of 1329 million was down 168 percent from 
the previous year 
ranked fifth again was gordy co the former motown industries 
inc with sales of 100 million 
computer and office supply companies accounted for 18 of the 
biggest 100 industrial and service businesses followed by 17 
manufacturing companies 16 food and beverage companies and 10 
media companies 
california led all states with 23 of the companies belonging to 
one or the other of the two top100 lists michigan had 22 
followed by new york with 19 illinois with 17 ohio with 13 and 
texas with 11 
