<TEXT>
japan with some of the most expensive real estate 
in the world could suffer economic problems if land prices fall as 
history indicates they might the bank of japan said wednesday 
experiences abroad suggest that it is important to forestall 
any turbulence which might arise from a sudden change in land 
prices in order to maintain a safe and sound financial system 
the central bank said in a report 
land prices in tokyo jumped 238 percent in 1987 and 653 
percent in 1988 before the increase slowed to less than 2 percent 
last year according to the national land agency 
nationwide land prices soared 17 percent in 1989 after a 217 
rise in 1988 as speculative inflation spread to other japanese 
cities 
the most expensive commercial property in the world in central 
tokyos marunouchi and ginza business districts was valued at 
23700 a square foot the agency said 
the bank of japan said history shows that it is wrong to assume 
land prices will keep climbing and never decline this assumption 
among corporate and individual investors is driving economic 
decisions and poses a risk to the economy it said 
the bank called for legal and tax reforms to end incentives for 
property speculation and encourage more efficient land use 
meanwhile it said financial institutions should be monitored 
closely to ensure that a drop in land prices doesnt undermine the 
value of the currency 
the scarcity of land is one basic factor behind the high prices 
but more fundamentally institutional factors such as the tax 
and legal systems seem to work to push up land prices by inhibiting 
the more efficient utilization of land the bank of japan said 
it said cases in the united states and britain show that when 
land prices climb steeply over a short period they may decline 
harming financial institutions such as savings and loan firms 
involved in property lending 
a sudden decline in land prices could be triggered by tighter 
monetary policy which raises interest rates as well as changes in 
the economy and legal and tax systems the bank said 
rising prices in other areas have led the bank to raise its 
official discount rate four times in the past year to its current 
525 percent from a historic low of 25 percent the rate is what 
commercial banks pay to borrow from the central bank 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

