<DOCNO> AP900509-0263 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
membersonly warehouse clubs introduced more 
than a decade ago to allow buyers to purchase office food and 
household goods in bulk have emerged as the retail industrys 
fastest growing sector 
sales at the estimated 600 clubs nationwide which target small 
businesses churches and nonprofit groups with the lure of 
wholesale purchases previously available only to large companies 
are projected to reach 25 billion this year a tenfold increase 
over 1984 
it took about five years for people to realize the concept was 
viable said arthur markowitz senior editor of the trade 
publication discount store news which has monitored the growth of 
clubs its a discount store for businessmen 
for an annual fee of about 25 club members are offered goods 
ranging from peanut butter to fax machines in large buildings that 
look more like construction warehouses than retail outlets 
the draw of the nofrills clubs industry officials say is that 
small businesses can save by buying goods at near wholesale prices 
for that reason the glitter of regular department store chains is 
unneeded and unwanted 
our member is a very intelligent consumer said john f 
geisse founder and chief executive of indianapolisbased wholesale 
club which operates 24 warehouses in the midwest youd better 
have the right item at the right time the best price and make sure 
its presented properly 
finding the right way to present the clubs to the target 
consumer was a matter of finetuning particularly in the midwest 
where geisse was working 
it was rather rough in the early years he said we opened 
west allis in suburban milwaukee and had a fabulous grand 
opening but people didnt come back i dont think we did our 
homework well this was only our third unit 
that was in 1984 when industry sales nationwide were about 24 
billion for 79 warehouses according to discount store news geisse 
said defining the products for small businesses was the key to 
overcoming three profitless years and opening 21 new warehouses 
since 1984 
discount store news estimates the warehouse clubs are the 
fastest growing sector of the retail industry with annual sales 
increases ranging from 140 percent to 26 percent over the last five 
years sales advances in other areas of retailing have been much 
more modest 
stephen mandel a securities analyst with new yorkbased 
investment bank goldman sachs and co agreed with the warehouse 
clubs emerging prominence in the retail industry he said small 
business owners churches and nonprofit organizations attacted by 
prices typically 9 percent over manufacturers cost are fueling the 
growth 
what makes the warehouse clubs stand out even more is the 
trouble that other parts of the retail business have been facing 
recently because of large debts rapid expansion and overly 
optimistic forecasts of aggressive spending by consumers who now 
seem to be holding back because of economic uncertainty 
some of the swankest department stores such as bloomingdales 
and jordan marsh now operate under bankruptcycourt protection 
because of parent company financial crises even a few big 
discounters have sought bankruptcy refuge most notably the ames 
department stores inc chain last month 
unlike discount stores which offer about 50000 items 
warehouse clubs sell only about 4000 items specific to small 
business needs at near wholesale prices markowitz said 
also unlike other retailers that operate on profit margins of 
more than 20 percent membership warehouse clubs operate on a 10 
percent profit margin because they offer a limited assortment of 
fast turning items markowitz said 
the clubs carry staple items and basic office supplies like 
sugar and copier paper on a regular basis but beyond that members 
dont know what they might find on any given visit 
the whole concept of buying is different said cathy roper 
community relations manager for the pace warehouse chain based in 
aurora colo were able to negotiate some bulktype deals with 
our vendors unlike a retailer that will get the same items again 
and again 
the clubs combine wholesale and retail by buying items for 
business use in bulk and carrying a few fastturning consumer items 
for their customers personal use like dress shirts and 
electronics markowitz said 
if an item moves slowly the club wont carry it again he said 
thats the only thing that matters to them if it sells he 
said since theyre not locked into anything they can go into 
wherever they can sell merchandise 
the clubs also keep costs low by avoiding members whose checks 
might not always clear and by refusing to accept credit cards if 
theres a margin of only 10 percent they cant afford to pay two 
or three percent of that to visa or mastercard markowitz said 
the clubs were introduced in the united states in 1976 when the 
price co opened its first price club in san diego the company now 
has 48 warehouses nationwide said giles bateman vice chairman 
price cos founder sol price got the idea for the warehouses 
from huge cashandcarry stores popular in europe markowitz 
said 
the price club began expanding rapidly after the first unit but 
other companies didnt seize the market for several years 
markowitz said 
pace entered the industry in 1982 and now has 54 stores in 15 
states ms roper said adding the companys expansion has not 
slowed 
discount store news projects continued growth for the entire 
industry markowitz said states in the northeast hold extraordinary 
potential 
in california in the los angeles market you have about 30 
stores he said but in the 1012state northeast region in 
the entire market they only have about 30 stores theres still a 
lot of growth because theres still a lot of areas where there 
arent many of them 
</TEXT>
