<TEXT>
the governments top telephone regulator said 
wednesday he can safely control the huge regional bell telephone 
companies if they are allowed to design and manufacture telephone 
equipment 
but bell rivals and consumer groups told a senate hearing they 
were concerned bell companies could drive out competition and 
subsidize new business ventures with their monopoly local telephone 
earnings 
a bill by sen ernest f hollings dsc would lift 
manufacturing restrictions imposed on the seven regional bell 
companies by a court ruling that ended an american telephone amp 
telegraph co antitrust suit in 1984 
the hollings bill would allow the bells to design develop and 
make telecommunications equipment including network and customer 
premises equipment 
it also has provisions requiring that such activities take place 
in the united states and assuring against crosssubsidies 
the fccs admitted inability to fully monitor the business 
practices of atampt led to the federal consent decree in which atampt 
in 1984 spun off the regional bells 
but fcc chairman alfred sikes told the senate commerce science 
and transportation subcommittee on communications that the fcc 
with an increased budget and new price regulatory scheme was 
prepared to monitor bell manufacturing activities 
existing pending and proposed fcc and state regulatory 
safeguards will be adequate to safeguard the interests of telephone 
ratepayers and potential bell company manufacturing competitors 
sikes said 
sikes said the fcc also is aided now by bell competitors eager 
to blow the whistle on any bell missteps 
but gene kimmelman legislative director of the consumer 
federation of america said lifting the manufacturing restrictions 
could mean substantial local rate increases and diminished 
competition in return for theoretical vaguely articulated 
benefits 
albert kramer general counsel of the north american 
telecommunications association said his group of equipment 
manufacturers and distributors opposes the bill because it would 
not improve competitiveness 
hollings said he was not sure when he would try to advance the 
bill a similar version is pending in the house of representatives 
previous efforts to free the bells from restrictions have not 
advanced in congress but the bells have launched a 
multimilliondollar campaign this year to try to swing public and 
congressional opinion to their side 
