<TEXT>
the governments prosecution of three commodity 
traders is simply a case about fraud a federal prosecutor said 
wednesday at the first trial resulting from an fbi probe at the 
worlds largest futures exchanges 
assistant us attorney mark pollack cautioned the jury in 
opening remarks at the us district court trial not to be 
distracted by the unfamiliar rules and intricate mechanics of 
futures trading 
these are not complicated crimes pollack said these are 
simple crimes that occurred in a complex setting 
stripped to its barest essentials the evidence will 
demonstrate that this is a case about fraud he said 
defendants robert d mosky danny l scheck and david zatz are 
accused of defrauding public customers as they traded swiss franc 
futures at the chicago mercantile exchange 
they are the first to go on trial of 47 traders and a clerk 
indicted last year after an unprecedented fbi sting operation at 
the merc and the chicago board of trade the worlds two largest 
commodity futures exchanges 
defense lawyers were to make their opening statements thursday 
morning followed by the first prosecution witness an official of 
the federal commodity futures trading commission the cftc 
regulates futures trading 
pollack began his opening statement after 12 jurors and five 
alternates were chosen in a morning session before us district 
judge ann c williams 
the three defendants were motivated by greed pure and 
simple he said 
a thief who plies his trade in the guise of a bright trading 
jacket and uses a deck of customer orders is no less a thief than a 
common cat burglar the prosecutor said 
pollack devoted much of his statement to explaining the basics 
of futures trading educating the jury could prove a daunting task 
in the trial expected to last about six weeks 
the prosecutor also told jurors they would hear conversations 
about illegal trading secretly recorded by fbi agent randall 
jannett who posed as a corrupt trader 
among the recorded comments the jury will hear pollack said is 
a statement mosky allegedly made to jannett that good things 
happen to those who help out 
pollack said mosky made the remark after jannett agreed to a 
trade that deprived a customer of a profit opportunity 
that phrase captures the essence of what this case is all 
about pollack said ill help you you help me well each 
make money at the expense of the unwitting customer 
mosky faces charges of racketeering conspiracy 28 counts of 
mail or wire fraud and 51 counts of violating federal 
futurestrading rules if convicted on all counts he could be 
sentenced to 415 years in prison and fined 124 million 
zatz and scheck are charged with more than a dozen counts each 
of mail or wire fraud and trading violations they face maxiumum 
sentences of 70 years and 90 years in prison and fines of 21 
million and 3 million respectively 
sixteen of those indicted have pleaded guilty to reduced charges 
in return for their cooperation 
the governments case hinges on the testimony of two traders who 
worked with the defendants and have pleaded guilty to fraud 
charges and on the observations and taperecorded evidence 
gathered by jannett 
a swiss franc future is a contract to buy or sell a specified 
amount of the currency at a future date at a price agreed upon in 
advance 
banks and multinational businesses trade currency futures as 
insurance against foreign exchange losses futures contracts also 
are traded by speculators seeking to profit from the constantly 
changing prices 
</TEXT>
