<TEXT>
the state of florida moved wednesday to join 
the st petersburg times in a legal battle over stock dividends 
with a shareholder group led by texas billionaire robert m bass 
attorney general bob butterworth filed a motion to intervene in 
us district court in tampa saying he wanted to help fend off an 
attack by profiteers 
his action fulfilled a promise in march to join the times in the 
case 
the bass group known as the poynterjamison ventures limited 
partnership filed suit in february against the times publishing 
co and the poynter institute a nonprofit journalism school that 
uses times stock dividends to support its operations 
the bass group owns 40 percent of the companys voting stock but 
receives only 57 percent of its dividends the poynter institute 
owns a majority of the voting stock and receives 83 percent of the 
dividends by virtue of its control of most of the companys 
preferred stock 
the bass group wants to change the stock structure to get a 
better return on its investment times publishing defends the stock 
arrangement as beneficial to the journalistic standards of the 
newspaper and the health of poynter institute 
the relief sought by the ventures partners would significantly 
diminish the future resources of the poynter institute 
butterworth said 
the attorney general has determined that it is important to 
florida public policy to protect such arrangements from attack by 
profiteers 
also butterworth said he wanted to send a message to 
reassure those persons who desire to give money to charities that 
their request and wishes will be honored by the state of florida 
and that the state will not permit charitable bequests to be 
usurped by outside speculators and interlopers 
the bass group includes relatives of the late nelson poynter 
who founded the institute and set up the unusual stock arrangement 
</TEXT>
